  "Grid"]], "Output",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.9925173401039124`*^9},
 CellLabel->"Out[6]=",ExpressionUUID->"7470c36a-4117-45b1-9aa7-8e67f9cd8a00"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["\<\
Zonal harmonics (m = 0, left column) are pure latitude bands. As m grows \
toward l (right column) the pattern breaks into longitudinal stripes; the \
sectoral harmonics m = l are the axis-aligned bands. Rotating 3-D convection \
does tend to favour axis-aligned structures, but that selection is a Taylor\
\[Dash]Proudman effect the 2-D model lacks. Here these are just basis \
functions, shown to build intuition for the (l, m) indexing.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"aeb63692-c9b0-4bd8-9034-1736ffd5b9b0"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2.5  The Jacobian: nonlinear advection, computed spectrally", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a2df3804-1aa1-4432-8a10-bd7fbcde5825"],

Cell["\<\
The advection term is the Jacobian operator, which on the unit sphere is\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e919f104-fedd-4cf8-9063-ea58e379a506"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"J", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"A", ",", "B"}], ")"}], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "A"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Phi]"}]], 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "B"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Lambda]"}]], "-", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "A"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Lambda]"}]], 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "B"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Phi]"}]]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"fcca5e68-125b-424f-b101-43ca0524b011"],

Cell["\<\
with \[Lambda] longitude and \[Phi] latitude. Geometrically J(A, B) measures \
how much the contours of A and B cross: it is the rate at which the flow \
along contours of A advects the field B. Setting A = \[Psi] and B = \
\[Omega]+f gives the advection of absolute vorticity by the streamfunction \
flow.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6aa1f373-4be4-4e22-a181-be2bf4990949"],

Cell["\<\
A pseudo-spectral evaluation is the standard trick and exactly what \
simulate_v6.py does. Products are cheap in physical (grid) space; derivatives \
are cheap in spectral space. So each step:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b41d516f-ca2a-4164-8a2e-27afdb680090"],

Cell["\<\
1. Transform \[Psi] and \[Omega]+f to spectral coefficients; multiply by the \
appropriate wavenumbers to get the horizontal gradients.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ad09df5b-d58e-4a97-9040-0b9e9302dfbb"],

Cell["2. Transform those gradient fields back to the grid.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"d33dea85-f976-4c55-8517-17faf5687605"],

Cell["\<\
3. Form the products and the difference pointwise on the grid \[Dash] this is \
J on the grid.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"76597796-fae2-4432-a9e2-37da63c1cf1d"],

Cell["\<\
4. Transform the result back to spectral space for the time step.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9ca313ed-cba7-4d05-8927-0bd71b0c95e7"],

Cell["\<\
The forward/inverse spherical-harmonic transforms are the workhorse; \
everything else is elementwise arithmetic. (pyshtools performs the \
transforms; the code multiplies gradient components exactly as in the formula \
above.)\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e04a3988-25b1-40c2-9844-5498304d8282"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["3.  Key Dimensionless Numbers", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"246e4729-0d9c-4353-b310-ca2c52a23d1c"],

Cell["\<\
Whether convection is rotation-dominated, and what structures it forms, is \
decided by a handful of dimensionless ratios. They compare the competing \
forces \[Dash] buoyancy, rotation, viscosity, thermal diffusion \[Dash] and \
locate the flow in parameter space.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6e63466e-8ba2-4600-bc43-b273946ee6a4"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["3.1  The four governing numbers", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"60109242-eb0d-4f58-baa5-1f83177c5fdc"],

Cell["\<\
Let d be the shell thickness, \[CapitalDelta]T the superadiabatic temperature \
contrast, g gravity, \[Alpha] the thermal expansion coefficient, \[Nu] \
kinematic viscosity, \[Kappa] thermal diffusivity, \[CapitalOmega] the \
rotation rate, and U, L a characteristic velocity and length of the flow.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"bf751d19-9b99-45a7-a261-4ecc7d078347"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Rayleigh number \[Dash] buoyancy vs diffusion", "Subsubsection",ExpressionUUID->"47f8eaa3-03ef-41ae-a9af-7404ca9d645a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"Ra", "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"g", " ", "\[Alpha]", " ", "\[CapitalDelta]T", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["d", "3"]}], 
    RowBox[{"\[Nu]", " ", "\[Kappa]"}]]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"8c89ef2f-43ca-45db-8052-905ff64829ae"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The ratio of buoyant driving to the damping of viscosity and thermal \
diffusion. Above a critical value convection sets in; the Sun runs at Ra ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   RowBox[{"\[TildeTilde]", "10"}], 
   RowBox[{"20", "\[Dash]", "24"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "981296f1-f5bd-45b9-bac0-783596562c74"],
 ", stupendously supercritical \[Dash] fully turbulent."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a72bcd30-0faf-4b46-8423-bf37830fa5da"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Ekman number \[Dash] viscosity vs rotation", "Subsubsection",ExpressionUUID->"40da7177-d742-4d5e-bc78-13d3199210c8"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"Ek", "=", 
   FractionBox["\[Nu]", 
    RowBox[{"2", " ", "\[CapitalOmega]", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["d", "2"]}]]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"6ff719fb-d613-46a4-953b-5a5465cfc892"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The ratio of viscous to Coriolis forces. The solar value is minuscule, Ek \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   RowBox[{"\[TildeTilde]", "10"}], 
   RowBox[{"-", "15"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "23f28b15-727b-4c8f-b5ae-daafa5640152"],
 " or smaller: rotation utterly dominates viscosity. Small Ek is the hallmark \
of a rapidly rotating system."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d65b173c-5ba7-4d42-9fa9-2fcc09e90f10"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Prandtl number \[Dash] momentum vs heat diffusion", "Subsubsection",ExpressionUUID->"a444b5c5-c697-4bee-94e3-0a94b4e3c84d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"Pr", "=", 
   FractionBox["\[Nu]", "\[Kappa]"]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"27f5d930-6c58-49eb-a8c0-aecd08434365"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A property of the fluid itself. In stellar plasma Pr ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   RowBox[{"\[TildeTilde]", "10"}], 
   RowBox[{"-", "6"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "33ef278d-0cc6-4b01-90fb-27c017f5a1b8"],
 " (heat diffuses far faster than momentum), though most simulations, ours \
included, use an effective turbulent Pr of order unity."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cc397cb1-a2d8-45d0-9ceb-11d19bea3d99"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Rossby number \[Dash] inertia vs rotation", "Subsubsection",ExpressionUUID->"40c10026-261a-4a78-8217-63ea22cacb5f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"Ro", "=", 
   FractionBox["U", 
    RowBox[{"2", " ", "\[CapitalOmega]", " ", "L"}]]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"09439336-e977-4dc8-80ae-366a02a04c75"],

Cell["\<\
The single most diagnostic number for the flow structure. Ro \[LessLess] 1 \
means the Coriolis force dominates fluid inertia and the flow is strongly \
rotationally constrained. The solar convection zone has Ro \[TildeTilde] 0.1\
\[Dash]1 depending on scale: the large scales are rotationally constrained, \
the small granular scales are not. The model is run at high \[CapitalOmega] \
(= 40 here), which does place the resolved flow at low Rossby number (Ro \
\[TildeTilde] 0.06 at the forcing scale). But low Ro alone does not hand a \
2-D model the axis-aligned columns of 3-D rotating convection \[Dash] that \
requires the Taylor\[Dash]Proudman constraint (Section 3.2), which is absent \
here. In practice the run stays close to isotropic, with only ~3.7% of its \
energy in zonal (m = 0) modes (Section 6).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"069373b4-a1ef-41ba-92d0-af433f61dc89"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["3.2  The Taylor\[Dash]Proudman theorem", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"736d30e3-f587-4c1a-8768-c2f54144e8ed"],

Cell["\<\
Why does rapid rotation produce columns? Consider a steady, slow, inviscid \
flow. In the rotating frame the leading-order momentum balance is between the \
Coriolis force and the pressure gradient \[Dash] geostrophic balance:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"db6ac6d3-3299-4043-a326-c94c9297f071"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"2", " ", 
   OverscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "\[RightVector]"], "\[Cross]", 
   OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "=", "-", 
   FractionBox["1", "\[Rho]"], 
   RowBox[{"\[Del]", "p"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"b9e130e9-2452-4a30-9d1e-c951fc260a44"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Take the curl of both sides. The right-hand side vanishes (the curl of a \
gradient is zero, for constant \[Rho]), and with \[Del]\[CenterDot]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "34597b5e-2146-42dc-82ff-a401930af2bf"],
 " = 0 the left side collapses to a beautifully simple statement:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"125cd45a-2614-440e-aacd-9f95e7d2aa9e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", 
     "\[Del]"}], ")"}], 
   OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "=", "0"}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"5dc10703-a17a-4028-9256-efd7ab3aa726"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The velocity field cannot vary along the direction of the rotation axis. If \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c244ce88-62c0-4006-88d1-b7e7f885caab"],
 " points along ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["z", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "45e15842-719c-4f9c-b70d-083da1459fdb"],
 ", then \[PartialD]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "38d8728c-4819-4485-a6a4-8dce47d0d2b0"],
 "/\[PartialD]z = 0: the flow is two-dimensional, identical on every plane \
perpendicular to the axis. This is the Taylor\[Dash]Proudman theorem. A \
rotating fluid is \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]stiff\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] along \
the axis \[Dash] it moves in rigid columns known as Taylor columns."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8fa657ba-ac0c-40a9-b783-c9ace51322bc"],

Cell["\<\
In a sphere, convection constrained to remain columnar wraps these columns \
around the inner core, producing the north\[Dash]south elongated \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]banana cells\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] first described \
by Busse (1970). It is tempting to argue that this justifies a 2-D model: if \
rapid rotation makes the 3-D flow nearly two-dimensional, why not model it in \
2-D directly? The argument fails on a crucial point. Taylor\[Dash]Proudman \
makes the flow invariant ALONG the rotation axis \[Dash] a direction that \
lies in the equatorial PLANE, not on the spherical surface this barotropic \
model uses. The model here evolves vorticity on a sphere; it has no axis to \
be stiff along and cannot represent Taylor columns at all. The derivation \
below is background for why rotating convection is columnar in reality \
\[Dash] not a mechanism present in this model.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8903beaf-da8b-450c-936e-1633131e66c0"],

Cell["\<\
The cell below makes the constraint visible: convection columns aligned with \
the rotation axis, wrapping the tangent cylinder that circumscribes the inner \
core. This illustrates the real 3-D geometry \[Dash] which the 2-D surface \
model does not contain.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"30a0471e-aed8-4c5d-bf00-77e0964d1ddc"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Module[{axis, tanCyl, columns, sph, nCol = 14, rIn = 0.35},
 sph = {Opacity[0.08], Gray, Sphere[{0, 0, 0}, 1]};
 axis = {Thick, Black, Arrow[Tube[{{0, 0, -1.25}, {0, 0, 1.35}}, 0.006]]};
 (* tangent cylinder: circumscribes the inner core *)
 tanCyl = {Opacity[0.12], Blue,
   Cylinder[{{0, 0, -Sqrt[1 - rIn^2]}, {0, 0, Sqrt[1 - rIn^2]}}, rIn]};
 (* banana columns just outside the tangent cylinder *)
 columns = Table[
   With[{s = 0.62, a = 2 Pi k/nCol},
    {ColorData[\"TemperatureMap\"][Mod[k, 2]], Opacity[0.85],
     Cylinder[{{s Cos[a], s Sin[a], -Sqrt[1 - s^2]},
       {s Cos[a], s Sin[a], Sqrt[1 - s^2]}}, 0.05]}],
   {k, 0, nCol - 1}];
 Graphics3D[{sph, tanCyl, columns, axis,
   Text[Style[\"\[CapitalOmega]\", 16, Bold], {0, 0, 1.45}]},
  Boxed -> False, ImageSize -> 400, ViewPoint -> {2.4, -1.8, 1.3},
  PlotLabel -> Style[\"Taylor columns aligned with the rotation axis\", 13, \
Bold]]]\
\>", "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[7]:=",ExpressionUUID->"a514540b-af7f-4e4c-aa56-f816b07e7f80"],

