Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["5.2  The radial reconstruction on the cut faces", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"0ee6d460-306a-45a4-bf49-fd6c88b22538"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The barotropic model lives on a single spherical surface \[Dash] it has no \
genuine radial structure. To draw a cutaway we must nonetheless say something \
about \[Omega] INSIDE the shell. v6 replaces v5's decorative decay with the \
correct RADIAL EIGENFUNCTION: each spherical-harmonic mode is continued \
inward by the regular solid harmonic ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"r", "/", 
     SubscriptBox["R", "out"]}], ")"}], "l"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "3d777a47-e26e-4f9b-856d-497d347172f5"],
 " \[Dash] the solution of Laplace's equation \[Del]^2(",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["r", "l"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7ee52fd3-fde0-4d14-90ca-60b419bc8c1d"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubsuperscriptBox["Y", "l", "m"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4a4814a6-63bb-4561-ad56-a6848efb91ad"],
 ") = 0 that stays finite toward the origin, hence the natural radial \
structure of a harmonic scalar field. Written per mode:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"625137ed-ef1a-401f-8121-efc32d48fd7c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[Omega]", "(", 
    RowBox[{"r", ",", "\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{"l", ",", "m"}]], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "l", "m"], " ", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"r", "/", 
       SubscriptBox["R", "out"]}], ")"}], "l"], " ", 
    RowBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["Y", "l", "m"], "(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"b9c8701e-cbce-416a-a482-b76f3af6299f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The factor ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"r", "/", 
     SubscriptBox["R", "out"]}], ")"}], "l"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "259befa8-08d6-4a45-9032-6ad84cbe3391"],
 " does two honest things at once. At r = ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox["R", "out"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a74768ea-f24f-482a-a2d5-0ab0afb67351"],
 " it equals 1, so the cut faces join the coloured surface seamlessly \[Dash] \
no longitude shear needed. And because it decays faster the larger l is, \
low-l (large-scale) structures reach deep into the shell while high-l \
filaments stay surface-confined \[Dash] the depth ordering is DERIVED from \
the harmonic degree, not painted on. The plot shows the weight for a few \
degrees; note how completely the forcing scale (l \[TildeTilde] 70) dies \
before reaching the base at r/R = 0.71."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"174675d9-d457-4e59-9699-d9ddf5c0b2e2"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Module[{rIn = 0.71, rOut = 1.0, ls = {2, 6, 20, 70}},
 Plot[Evaluate[Table[(r/rOut)^l, {l, ls}]], {r, rIn, rOut},
  PlotRange -> {0, 1}, PlotStyle -> {Red, Purple, Darker[Green], Blue},
  Frame -> True, FrameLabel -> {\"radius r / R\", \"radial weight (r/R)^l\"},
  PlotLegends -> ((\"l = \" <> ToString[#]) & /@ ls),
  GridLines -> {{rIn, rOut}, {0, 1}}, ImageSize -> 440,
  PlotLabel -> Style[\"Regular solid-harmonic radial weight (r/R)^l\", 13, \
Bold]]]\
\>", "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[16]:=",ExpressionUUID->"f13ff939-5a21-4bc9-8a41-5fb4af2e1712"],

