 CellChangeTimes->{3.992517341390802*^9},
 CellLabel->"Out[19]=",ExpressionUUID->"f83782df-4488-4ce8-b314-ff6059129e43"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["6.3  What the model gets right \[Dash] and what it misses", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"60f68f32-4928-41e8-adb1-fd6a915da2a5"],

Cell["Gets right:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"10f28629-a2fc-44be-a9cf-cdbadbddc615"],

Cell["\<\
Rotation-dominated 2-D dynamics. The Coriolis \[Beta]-effect is represented \
exactly, and the resolved flow sits at low Rossby number.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"720307d6-e153-4eb6-ad7e-9096c857b7a7"],

Cell["\<\
The kinematics of non-divergent flow on a rotating sphere: exact vorticity\
\[Dash]streamfunction inversion, planetary-vorticity advection, and \
Rossby-wave propagation.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"1c63451b-dfac-4f42-9840-97fcdc85f0eb"],

Cell["\<\
The character of forced\[Dash]dissipative 2-D turbulence: a dual cascade \
(forward enstrophy to filaments, some inverse energy transfer), \
filamentation, and a statistically steady state.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"278affe5-f93d-4a56-b6c2-c97c8e8efc99"],

Cell["Misses:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ddcb3632-dbcb-4f4f-9142-5f8c62161bd4"],

Cell["\<\
Radial structure. There is no genuine depth dependence; the interior in the \
visualisation is a mapping, not a solution. Real convection has plumes \
spanning the depth of the zone.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"868c1809-8834-453a-8cc6-3a5a0bc185b0"],

Cell["\<\
Differential rotation. The solar equator-fast profile emerges from the \
interaction of convection, rotation, and the meridional circulation \[Dash] \
mean flows the barotropic model cannot self-consistently generate.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"1f5d7943-4fe8-41ae-b854-58c248195e2f"],

Cell["\<\
Thermal physics and stratification. No temperature equation, no density \
stratification (which makes upflows broad and downflows narrow in the real \
Sun), no superadiabaticity.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"f747c62d-400e-4445-bbc3-28b90994e492"],

Cell["\<\
Magnetism. No dynamo, hence no sunspot cycle \[Dash] the phenomenon that \
motivates much of solar-convection research.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"451b535e-7f5f-4ae6-866f-eaa42c2c9762"],

Cell["\<\
The barotropic model is best understood as a fast, transparent laboratory for \
the geometry and statistics of forced 2-D turbulence on a rotating sphere \
\[Dash] not a model of solar convection, and (at these parameters) not even a \
jet-forming geostrophic-turbulence run. It is a stepping stone to, not a \
replacement for, the full 3-D simulations described next.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"68b3b004-4767-4001-be95-74670df68d15"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["7.  What This Model Cannot Capture", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"07f0c919-7e38-454d-b47d-19726c406745"],

Cell["\<\
The limitations below are STRUCTURAL \[Dash] they follow from the model being \
a single scalar equation on a 2-D surface, and no amount of parameter tuning \
can remove them. This is the honest boundary of what a barotropic vorticity \
model can say about solar convection.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cc0df460-0abd-4bc9-853d-d352358260f5"],

Cell["\<\
No radial dimension. The model lives on one spherical surface, so it has no \
depth structure, no penetration or overshoot, no tachocline, and no vertical \
velocity \[Dash] which is precisely the up/down-flow signal that convection \
imagery shows. The interior in the cutaway is a kinematic reconstruction \
(Section 5), not a solved flow.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"954efb29-25bb-4558-8cf0-8655f5a8bc79"],

Cell["\<\
No buoyancy or energy equation. There is no temperature, no Rayleigh number, \
no convective instability, and no heat transport. The flow is stirred by \
imposed forcing, not driven by buoyancy; the convective scale is prescribed, \
not selected.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"3dfdd720-5670-410d-a408-dd4b6c217313"],

Cell["\<\
No stratification or compressibility. The real Sun spans ~4\[Dash]5 density \
scale heights, which makes upflows broad and downflows narrow; the barotropic \
model is incompressible and uniform.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b38ee0f9-9294-4d36-b8ca-3df84ee52041"],

Cell["\<\
No Taylor\[Dash]Proudman constraint. This is a genuinely 3-D balance \
(invariance along the rotation axis), so real axis-aligned banana cells \
cannot arise from the correct mechanism in a 2-D surface model (Sections 1.2, \
3.2).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"d6b4af47-f7ad-4647-848c-0e56434cf497"],

Cell["\<\
No self-consistent differential rotation. The solar equator-fast profile \
emerges from correlated 3-D velocity components (Reynolds stresses, \
meridional circulation) that a single scalar \[Omega] cannot carry. The \
longitude twist on the cutaway faces is a viewing choice, not solar rotation.\
\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"dd57870e-c887-49d4-a847-928a323e6f1b"],

Cell["\<\
No magnetism. No induction, hence no dynamo, no 11-year cycle, and no \
sunspots \[Dash] the very phenomena that motivate much of solar-convection \
research. To model any of this you need a 3-D anelastic (MHD) code (see the \
References and README_v6.md).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"3deb0a60-d133-41f7-8f46-0099da3bcbe1"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["8.  The v6 Audit \[Dash] What Is Verified and What Is Not", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"5c08f7cf-21d3-45a4-8d0e-29d37ad3d131"],

Cell["\<\
v6 is a scientifically honest rebuild of an earlier v5 run whose physics \
claims did not survive scrutiny. Every checkable claim was re-derived and \
tested numerically against the saturated field (v6_critical_audit.md). The \
result is a clear split between a trustworthy SOLVER and a set of claims the \
field does NOT support.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6dd123a8-7ffb-427a-8669-4f8126b1da95"],

Cell["Verified correct (the numerics are sound):", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9c688ab7-4d79-47ff-87ed-b266fbba638c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The advection conserves energy and enstrophy to ~1\[Times]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["10", 
   RowBox[{"-", "6"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "22af5f05-678d-4222-997a-e9e0460fc7ca"],
 " per step in an inviscid test \[Dash] the strongest single piece of \
evidence that the barotropic Jacobian and time step are correct."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"dd4e055d-9925-4c70-a91c-dd3e3e1e2c24"],

Cell["\<\
The spherical Jacobian is metric-consistent (built from physical gradient \
components, avoiding the 1/cos\[Phi] singularity) and is effectively \
alias-free (0.07% vs a 2\[Times]-padded reference).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"1ee117ac-68c1-4b1c-b221-0dbc0cd50517"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The Coriolis coefficient is fixed to 2\[CapitalOmega]/",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SqrtBox["3"]],ExpressionUUID->"d61c2b18-122a-47f6-b077-da12060b4b5c"],
 ", giving f(pole) = 2\[CapitalOmega] = 80 exactly (Section 2.3.1); the \
\[Del]^8 hyperviscosity, the exact integrating-factor dissipation, and the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SqrtBox["\[CapitalDelta]t"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5dd7a609-c93e-4b42-837b-2cd390482635"],
 " white-noise forcing scaling all check out."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"fde3622f-1d4c-4ba0-ae42-5ef058a7abfb"],

Cell["\<\
Not achieved / honest caveats (properties of the run, not bugs in the solver):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9fc1f0b4-672f-4c56-8eae-6676b9fbecbf"],

Cell["\<\
Jets are NOT achieved. Zonal energy is ~3.7% \[Dash] essentially isotropic \
turbulence. The cascade broadened (a real improvement over v5), but the \
marginal Rhines/forcing separation (l_R \[TildeTilde] 23 vs forcing \
60\[Dash]80) and the ~42% energy loss to hyperviscosity keep the inverse \
cascade too weak to organise jets.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"65efd6b3-88e9-47de-92bc-44a756f3acda"],

Cell["\<\
The time integration is globally O(\[CapitalDelta]t) (first-order Lie split \
of a Heun advection step with an exact linear factor), not 2nd-order \[Dash] \
verified by a step-halving ratio of 2.00 (Section 4.3).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"5a25310c-bbc0-4dc9-b34b-2d54ebe3d2f3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The interior reconstruction and the cutaway longitude twist are \
illustrative geometry, not solved dynamics; the display softens the true ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"r", "/", "R"}], ")"}], "l"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "49add919-a7ac-4911-b449-4245e165181b"],
 " decay and so overstates deep penetration of forcing-scale modes by ~10\
\[Times] (Section 5.2). All of this is honestly labelled in the code and \
captions."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"e3538899-e091-45d2-84ed-8003b9bc215e"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Part II \[LongDash] The Full Physics Programme: All Twenty Improvements\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"62a74898-d060-4374-8c81-f6bb17602574"],

Cell["\<\
Sections 1\[Dash]8 above document the v6 barotropic solver. The project has \
since been extended through twenty scientific improvements \
(scientific_improvements.md), grouped in four tiers: (A) make the barotropic \
model actually demonstrate the physics it claims (items 1\[Dash]8 \[Dash] \
wider scale separation, steady-state averaging, higher-order time stepping, \
controlled forcing, flux diagnostics); (B) extend the physics with new terms \
and new equation sets (items 9\[Dash]14 \[Dash] differential rotation, \
topography, deformation radius, two-layer QG, shallow water, MHD); (C) \
replace the model with real convection (items 15\[Dash]18 \[Dash] Boussinesq \
and anelastic shells, community solvers, Model S stratification); and (D) \
turn output into evidence (items 19\[Dash]20 \[Dash] Lagrangian FTLE, honest \
interior). The sections below give the governing equations, the physical \
meaning of each term, the numerical method, and the key references for every \
improvement. The implementing modules are named in each section.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"153ec553-6969-4c9c-b852-96e7bace3308"],

Cell["\<\
Honesty note carried forward from Part I: items 1\[Dash]14 all evolve a 2-D \
scalar field on a surface and are NOT convection \[Dash] they have no \
buoyancy, no energy equation, no vertical velocity. Only items 15\[Dash]18 \
add genuine convection (buoyancy + temperature + a radial dimension). Every \
section states plainly what it does and does not contain.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5a2eb5e7-5080-4026-af2c-24709023fbb7"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["9.  The Complete Governing Equation and Its Spectral Form", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"2e582ea5-2f3b-4e7a-9377-49c991b9b5d0"],

Cell["\<\
The equation the v6/v7 barotropic solver integrates, written with every term \
(config_v7.py, simulate_v7.py):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b064a779-bf67-47ca-aeaf-a2060decea49"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Omega]"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
   RowBox[{"J", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ",", "\[Omega]", "+", "f"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", "\[Nu]", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"]}], ")"}], "4"], "\[Omega]"}], "-", 
   RowBox[{"\[Mu]", " ", "\[Omega]"}], "+", "F"}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"2ac41ca1-82ef-4dfd-bcd5-c1d504025cd5"],

Cell["Reading the terms as physical processes:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fa394549-b921-4a16-b0b5-9ea3f698b02c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[PartialD]\[Omega]/\[PartialD]t \[Dash] the local rate of change of the \
relative vertical vorticity \[Omega] = ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["z", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1d8218f8-c739-41cf-85d7-07010cae9b67"],
 "\[CenterDot](\[Del]\[Cross]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f3bee9f3-7c5f-498c-9641-e39e2510aff8"],
 "), the single prognostic scalar of the model."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"2d565b05-63a5-4df5-ad85-345e4e8dff4c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "J(\[Psi], \[Omega]+f) \[Dash] nonlinear advection of ABSOLUTE vorticity \
\[Omega]+f by the non-divergent flow ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "58dfb1b8-e168-420b-baea-e04af8807747"],
 " = ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["z", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "51331dfe-d568-4098-ad34-d556efe957ad"],
 "\[Cross]\[Del]\[Psi]. The advection of the PLANETARY part f by the eddies \
is the \[Beta]-effect; it is the term that makes Rossby waves and, \
ultimately, jets. This nonlinearity is what makes the problem turbulent."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"fe004e2d-9294-4339-83ee-7e839f71ddb4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Dash]\[Nu](\[Dash]\[Del]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", "2"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bb1dc947-4495-480d-88bb-2f5892ccf221"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", "4"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f3c9ca17-ab59-470c-a817-c9d605a27938"],
 "\[Omega] = \[Dash]\[Nu]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "8"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "117ea794-1da5-4814-bcf8-0e6485b6b5c4"],
 "\[Omega] \[Dash] \[Del]\[Cedilla] hyperviscosity. In spectral space it \
multiplies the coefficient by \[Dash]\[Nu]\[Lambda]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", "4"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "cd07cedf-962b-4860-8136-b9c5749495a6"],
 " with \[Lambda] = l(l+1); the drain time \[Tau] = 1/(\[Nu]\[Lambda]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", "4"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f2e501a3-219e-4106-b323-69c8a046c5af"],
 " is ~0.25 tu at the truncation but ~10",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["0", "6"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8b4dc729-7136-466c-83cc-547b15116944"],
 " tu at the jet scale, so it removes only the smallest scales (Section 4, \
config_v7 NU_HYPER)."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"03430b21-6e79-4943-b2f2-43e878abf949"],

Cell["\<\
\[Dash]\[Mu]\[Omega] \[Dash] uniform linear (Rayleigh / Ekman) drag, the \
PRIMARY large-scale energy sink. It sets the saturated energy E_sat = \
\[Epsilon]/(2\[Mu]) and arrests the inverse cascade; \[Tau]_drag = 1/\[Mu] is \
the flow's longest memory (100 tu in v7).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"5d9ff2b4-43ab-45ce-9224-9feda2bb2596"],

Cell["\<\
F \[Dash] stochastic forcing that injects vorticity in a chosen band of \
degrees. It is an imposed stirring, a kinematic stand-in for the convective \
plumes \[Dash] NOT buoyancy, and not selected by any instability (see Section \
11 for its statistics).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"280f4b2d-c4e5-447c-a01c-179f0051edfe"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["9.1  Vorticity\[Dash]streamfunction inversion", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"b640c89e-5d7b-4729-8ad6-9d5cafb13550"],

Cell["\<\
The flow is recovered from the vorticity by inverting the Laplacian. Because \
the spherical harmonics diagonalise \[Del]\.b2 (eigenvalue \[Dash]l(l+1), \
Section 4.1), the inversion is one division per mode:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c070b54c-2f45-4249-bfeb-534b0d20404c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"\[Omega]", "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Psi]", "\[LongRightArrow]", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "lm", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox[
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "lm", ""], 
     RowBox[{"l", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}]]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"c821fbad-880a-4839-9ed0-1583fe68b495"],

Cell["\<\
The equivalent-barotropic generalisation (Section 14.3) replaces the \
denominator l(l+1) by l(l+1)+1/L_d\.b2.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"da21e876-ce00-4f64-9e45-403f07f0a304"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["9.2  The Jacobian in physical and spectral space", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"6acac772-572a-4b7e-b68e-b834e561a592"],

Cell["\<\
The advection operator is the Jacobian of two scalars on the sphere,\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3bd80326-4ec1-42b1-b766-991154eadcbb"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"J", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ",", "B"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[CenterDot]", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Del]", "A", "\[Cross]", "\[Del]", "B"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[Cross]", "\[Del]", "A"}], ")"}], "\[CenterDot]",
     "\[Del]", "B"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"e0a7cfa0-ab3c-4a28-974b-4d8b02154f54"],

Cell["\<\
i.e. the advection of B by the flow whose streamfunction is A. The solver \
evaluates it PSEUDO-SPECTRALLY and metric-consistently: transform \[Psi] and \
\[Omega]+f to physical gradient components (\[PartialD]\[Theta], (1/sin\
\[Theta])\[PartialD]\[Phi]) with pyshtools, multiply on the grid to form the \
Jacobian, and transform back. Building it from physical gradient components \
(not raw \[PartialD]\[Phi]) avoids the 1/cos\[Phi] pole singularity and is \
alias-free on the oversampled Driscoll\[Dash]Healy grid (Section 8). The \
whole spectral update per mode is\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4b66fb64-24fc-4232-8ff5-884d5a2b4507"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "lm", ""]}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["N", "lm", ""], 
    RowBox[{"(", "\[Omega]", ")"}], "-", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"\[Mu]", "+", 
       RowBox[{"\[Nu]", 
        SuperscriptBox["\[Lambda]", "4"]}]}], ")"}], 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "lm", ""]}], "+", 
    SubsuperscriptBox["F", "lm", ""]}], ",", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", "=", 
    RowBox[{"l", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"c9cac85c-62be-44e1-aee2-8f38c5c9adc2"],

Cell["\<\
with N the spectral coefficients of \[Dash]J(\[Psi], \[Omega]+f). The linear \
part is diagonal (hence integrated exactly by an integrating factor or \
ETDRK4, Section 10); only N couples different modes.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cd9bedf9-7a6f-4ee8-9f5c-2c06b38209e6"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["9.3  The Coriolis coefficient and the \[Sqrt]3 normalisation", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"2c0ff53a-1dbf-48c9-86af-96705db573ef"],

Cell["\<\
The planetary vorticity f = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi] is a single spherical \
harmonic (l=1, m=0). Its spectral coefficient depends on the normalisation of \
the basis, and getting it wrong was the headline v5 bug. pyshtools uses REAL, \
4\[Pi]-normalised harmonics, in which\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ec1634d8-e3e4-4c17-85d1-36e8ecee8850"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["Y", "1", "0"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SqrtBox["3"], " ", "sin", "\[Phi]"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"a19cef9e-6dd3-4b8c-b790-8c0df4f0d57f"],

Cell["\<\
so to represent f = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi] the required coefficient is c \
with c\[ThinSpace]\[Sqrt]3\[ThinSpace]sin\[Phi] = 2\[CapitalOmega] sin\[Phi], \
i.e.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ac45d80d-0b17-441b-9428-57fc4cb3e1a5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["c", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", "0"}], ""], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]"}], 
    SqrtBox["3"]], "     ", "\[LongRightArrow]", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"f", "(", "pole", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"71ec2816-8006-42a1-90e3-a7fb83a35ddf"],

Cell["\<\
The \[Beta]-effect that arrests the inverse cascade is \[Beta] \[Congruent] \
df/dy at the equator = 2\[CapitalOmega] on the unit sphere. (v5 used the \
unit-normalised coefficient 2\[CapitalOmega]\[Sqrt](4\[Pi]/3) with \
4\[Pi]-normalised harmonics, inflating f by \[Sqrt](4\[Pi]) \[TildeTilde] 3.5\
\[Times]; v6/v7 fix it. A spectral coefficient is meaningless until the basis \
normalisation is stated.)\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fa63bfd9-cfca-484d-8be7-8dfb2a290d2e"],

Cell["\<\
References: Vallis (2017), Atmospheric and Oceanic Fluid Dynamics, 2nd ed. \
(CUP); Charney, Fj\[OSlash]rtoft & von Neumann (1950) Tellus 2, 237.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"db086e1b-1cc8-45e9-a430-eed5348b3877"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
10.  Numerical Methods: Operator Splitting and Exponential Integrators\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"a7bfb8a3-9161-468a-8195-b9ea1bfb0464"],

Cell["\<\
Improvements #3 and #4 (scientific_improvements.md \[Section]\[Section]3\
\[Dash]4). Split the vorticity equation into a stiff LINEAR part and a \
nonstiff NONLINEAR part:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fd8286e1-e22b-47fc-9810-a80d2714ca86"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Omega]"}], 
    RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
   RowBox[{"L", " ", "\[Omega]"}], "+", 
   RowBox[{"N", 
    RowBox[{"(", "\[Omega]", ")"}]}], ",", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"L", " ", "\[Omega]"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"-", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"\[Mu]", "+", 
       RowBox[{"\[Nu]", 
        SuperscriptBox["\[Lambda]", "4"]}]}], ")"}]}], "\[Omega]"}], ",", 
   "     ", 
   RowBox[{"N", 
    RowBox[{"(", "\[Omega]", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", "J", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ",", "\[Omega]", "+", "f"}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"f34f734c-d498-4abf-820b-0831e33268f0"],

Cell["\<\
L is DIAGONAL in spectral space (it just multiplies each mode by \
\[Dash](\[Mu]+\[Nu]\[Lambda]\.b3\.b3... )), so its exact flow exp(L\[Tau]) is \
known to machine precision \[Dash] no time-step restriction from the stiff \
hyperviscosity. The two schemes below differ only in how they combine this \
exact linear flow with an explicit treatment of N.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8bebd253-6905-47ec-b52d-99703de3e3d4"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["10.1  Strang (2nd-order) operator splitting", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"9f8c8dfa-f133-45eb-8889-1f09d10c2420"],

Cell["\<\
v6 used a Lie\[Dash]Trotter split (exact linear factor \[SmallCircle] Heun \
advection), which is only FIRST-order globally \[Dash] a verified \
step-halving error ratio of 2.0, and ~10% of the energy leaking anomalously \
to hyperviscosity. Symmetrising the composition recovers 2nd order at \
essentially no cost:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d6761f16-1da8-46f6-9715-54f7d4eab004"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"S", 
    RowBox[{"(", "dt", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"L", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      FractionBox["dt", "2"], ")"}]}], "\[CenterDot]", 
    RowBox[{"N", 
     RowBox[{"(", "dt", ")"}]}], "\[CenterDot]", 
    RowBox[{"L", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      FractionBox["dt", "2"], ")"}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"8f52ee72-69ee-4712-9c0b-1e8443337459"],

Cell["\<\
half-step exact linear flow \[SmallCircle] full-step Heun (RK2) advection \
\[SmallCircle] half-step exact linear flow. By the \
Baker\[Dash]Campbell\[Dash]Hausdorff expansion the leading splitting error of \
the ASYMMETRIC Lie product L(dt)\[CenterDot]N(dt) is the commutator term\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"895c9193-a919-4f8c-b627-4b395f887d57"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", "2"], 
   SuperscriptBox["dt", "2"], 
   RowBox[{"[", "L", ",", "N", "]"}], "+", 
   RowBox[{"O", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     SuperscriptBox["dt", "3"], ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"3913236c-266a-4ff5-9b9c-383ae49e1407"],

Cell["\<\
\[Dash] first order globally. Symmetrising cancels that commutator, leaving \
\[Dash](dt\.b3/24)([L,[L,N]]+2[N,[L,N]]) + \[Ellipsis], i.e. local error O(dt\
\.b3), global O(dt\.b2). This tightens the energy/enstrophy budget and \
permits larger stable steps. TIME_SCHEME='strang' is the v7 default.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"00d137ca-1f29-4386-a420-00251aa84358"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["10.2  ETDRK4: exponential time differencing", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"24789d82-46c1-454f-915a-b0e9098800aa"],

Cell["\<\
Because L is diagonal, an exponential integrator treats it EXACTLY while \
giving 4th-order accuracy on the nonlinear Jacobian (improvement #4). ETDRK4 \
(Cox & Matthews 2002; Kassam & Trefethen 2005) advances one step h=dt as four \
Jacobian evaluations:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"251b6dc4-d621-4fa8-b8e0-3c40baaafeea"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["N", "u", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"N", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["u", "n", ""], ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"a", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E2", "\[CenterDot]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["u", "n", ""]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{"Q", "\[CenterDot]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["N", "u", ""]}]}], ",", "  ", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["N", "a", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"N", 
       RowBox[{"(", "a", ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"b", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E2", "\[CenterDot]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["u", "n", ""]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{"Q", "\[CenterDot]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["N", "a", ""]}]}], ",", "  ", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["N", "b", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"N", 
       RowBox[{"(", "b", ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"c", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E2", "\[CenterDot]", "a"}], "+", 
       RowBox[{"Q", "\[CenterDot]", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"2", 
           SubsuperscriptBox["N", "b", ""]}], "-", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["N", "u", ""]}], ")"}]}]}], ",", "  ", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["N", "c", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"N", 
       RowBox[{"(", "c", ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["u", 
       RowBox[{"n", "+", "1"}], ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E", "\[CenterDot]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["u", "n", ""]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["N", "u", ""], 
        SubsuperscriptBox["f", "1", ""]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{"2", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{
          SubsuperscriptBox["N", "a", ""], "+", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["N", "b", ""]}], ")"}], 
        SubsuperscriptBox["f", "2", ""]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["N", "c", ""], 
        SubsuperscriptBox["f", "3", ""]}]}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"21a9aff8-5ac7-4ce8-8ecf-d307ea0685fa"],

Cell["with the exact-linear coefficients (h=dt, z=hL per mode)", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f4e185c9-c89c-4827-9be5-6006ee6ad67d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"E", "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["e", 
    RowBox[{"h", " ", "L"}]], ",", "   ", "E2", "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["e", 
    RowBox[{"h", " ", "L", "/", "2"}]], ",", "   ", "Q", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["h", "2"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "1", ""], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"h", " ", "L", "/", "2"}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"94f473e0-ea60-4d86-be00-0e9c1251d547"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["f", "1", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"h", " ", 
       RowBox[{"[", 
        RowBox[{"-", "4", "-", "z", "+", 
         RowBox[{
          SuperscriptBox["e", "z"], 
          RowBox[{"(", 
           RowBox[{"4", "-", "3", "z", "+", 
            SuperscriptBox["z", "2"]}], ")"}]}]}], "]"}], "/", 
       SuperscriptBox["z", "3"]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["f", "2", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"h", " ", 
       RowBox[{"[", 
        RowBox[{"2", "+", "z", "+", 
         RowBox[{
          SuperscriptBox["e", "z"], 
          RowBox[{"(", 
           RowBox[{"-", "2", "+", "z"}], ")"}]}]}], "]"}], "/", 
       SuperscriptBox["z", "3"]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["f", "3", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"h", " ", 
       RowBox[{"[", 
        RowBox[{"-", "4", "-", "3", "z", "-", 
         SuperscriptBox["z", "2"], "+", 
         RowBox[{
          SuperscriptBox["e", "z"], 
          RowBox[{"(", 
           RowBox[{"4", "-", "z"}], ")"}]}]}], "]"}], "/", 
       SuperscriptBox["z", "3"]}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"3252aa85-5794-4ae0-850e-7e022c36c9fe"],

Cell["\<\
When L\[RightArrow]0 the \[CurlyPhi]-functions reduce to E=E2=1 and the \
update collapses to classical RK4 \[Dash] ETDRK4 is the exact-linear analogue \
of RK4.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f641882f-1d38-43e0-8e59-c70b4f950d96"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["10.3  The Kassam\[Dash]Trefethen contour integral", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"26db12d5-93f1-44c1-aedd-cfb1685c1bdb"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Evaluated naively, the f_j quotients divide by z\.b3, and for our modes \
|z|=|L\[CenterDot]dt| \[LessTilde] 5\[Times]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["10", 
   RowBox[{"-", "3"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "342d89ff-a082-4a7a-bcf7-10fd3b721067"],
 " \[Dash] catastrophic cancellation (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["e", "z"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5e9b958d-ea04-4538-a9f6-681beab96e9b"],
 "\[Dash]1)/z \[Rule] 0/0 in floating point. Kassam & Trefethen (2005) \
average each \[CurlyPhi]-function over M points on a small circle around each \
eigenvalue, replacing the singular quotient by a well-conditioned Cauchy \
integral:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"41fe1995-7aa5-47e1-b61f-04f159ac9d98"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "j", ""], 
   RowBox[{"(", "z", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["1", 
     RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]", " ", "\[ImaginaryI]"}]], 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[ContourIntegral]", "\[Gamma]"], 
     FractionBox[
      RowBox[{
       SubsuperscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "j", ""], 
       RowBox[{"(", "t", ")"}]}], 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"t", "-", "z"}], ")"}]], 
     RowBox[{"\[DifferentialD]", "t"}]}]}], "\[TildeEqual]", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["1", "M"], 
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{"k", "=", "1"}], "M"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "j", ""], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"z", "+", 
      SuperscriptBox["r", " "], 
      SuperscriptBox["e", 
       RowBox[{"\[ImaginaryI]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["\[Theta]", "k", ""]}]]}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"7ce65831-1832-42df-9769-c3752e0063e0"],

Cell["\<\
with the M=32 roots-of-unity contour (config_v7 ETDRK4_M=32). This removes \
the cancellation and makes the exact-linear treatment robust. ETDRK4 costs ~4 \
Jacobian evaluations per step vs Strang's 2 (~2\[Times] the cost) but is far \
more accurate on the stiff linear term \[Dash] worth it at higher resolution \
or longer dt (TIME_SCHEME='etdrk4').\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a9152911-19fa-41de-bd6a-2a47f849c82b"],

Cell["\<\
References: Strang (1968) SIAM J. Numer. Anal. 5, 506; Cox & Matthews (2002) \
J. Comput. Phys. 176, 430; Kassam & Trefethen (2005) SIAM J. Sci. Comput. 26, \
1214; Ascher, Ruuth & Spiteri (1997) Appl. Numer. Math. 25, 151.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"122b08c4-c69b-4c1f-8318-6e8bb2e014be"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["11.  Physically-Grounded Stochastic Forcing", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"7849ae47-6293-425f-b95b-cdf01e71a6e5"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #5 (scientific_improvements.md \[Section]5). The forcing must \
inject a CONTROLLED energy rate \[Epsilon] in a chosen band, and optionally \
with a finite correlation time. config_v7 implements both.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"88c64207-bec8-472e-9340-2b2eb400aeab"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["11.1  Controlled energy-injection rate \[Epsilon]", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"aa88f068-28fa-4f95-b228-ef6874f09fb7"],

Cell["\<\
Each step adds an independent Gaussian increment \[Delta]\[Omega]_lm to every \
coefficient in the band [l_min, l_max], with per-coefficient standard \
deviation amp_l\[Sqrt]dt where amp_l = FORCE_AMP/\[Sqrt](l(l+1)). Because the \
increment is independent of the current field it adds enstrophy at rate amp_l\
\.b2 and energy at rate amp_l\.b2/(l(l+1)) per coefficient. Summing the \
(2l+1) real coefficients per degree gives the total energy-injection rate\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"786a40ab-ffb4-4412-b8be-4172ab442c2d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"\[Epsilon]", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{"l", "=", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["l", "min", ""]}], 
     SubsuperscriptBox["l", "max", ""]], 
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"2", "l", "+", "1"}], ")"}], 
      SuperscriptBox["amp", "l"], 
      SuperscriptBox[" ", "2"]}], 
     RowBox[{"l", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}]]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["FORCE_AMP", "2"], 
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{"l", "=", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["l", "min", ""]}], 
     SubsuperscriptBox["l", "max", ""]], 
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{"2", "l", "+", "1"}], 
     SuperscriptBox[
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"l", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}], ")"}], "2"]]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"dfeee1b3-2e81-461b-a2e0-e38200655592"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "So \[Epsilon] is fixed by the amplitude and band alone; inverting lets the \
code set FORCE_AMP = \[Sqrt](\[Epsilon]_target/S_band) from a TARGET rate \
rather than an arbitrary amplitude (config_v7 FORCE_FROM_EPSILON). \[Epsilon] \
matters because it fixes the frictional-arrest / jet-spacing scale k_fr ~ (\
\[Beta]\.b3/\[Epsilon])",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"1", "/", "5"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "fbaaaeba-fbda-4818-8b3d-9d3f3d89e66a"],
 " (Section 12)."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ea49e7d2-f457-4b9b-a1c4-622f017e95f7"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["11.2  Ornstein\[Dash]Uhlenbeck coloured forcing", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"167b5a29-5285-4532-8916-aebc42062b08"],

Cell["\<\
The 'white' branch is delta-correlated in time (a \[Sqrt]dt Wiener \
increment). The 'ou' branch instead evolves a persistent forcing field f_lm \
with a finite correlation time \[Tau]_c as the Ornstein\[Dash]Uhlenbeck \
process \[Dash] the unique stationary Gaussian Markov process:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b8f7dbdc-5044-4abd-b153-a77f42677113"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"d", 
    SubsuperscriptBox["f", "lm", ""]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox[
     SubsuperscriptBox["f", "lm", ""], 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "c", ""]], "dt"}], "+", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "l", ""], "dW"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"0eacc1c3-fb8b-4b29-b414-361a8e3a4f3e"],

Cell["Its stationary autocovariance is the exponential", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2e2bb8ad-da22-484e-a83c-22c292cc79c5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"C", 
    RowBox[{"(", "s", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"\[LeftAngleBracket]", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"f", 
      RowBox[{"(", "t", ")"}]}], " ", 
     RowBox[{"f", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"t", "+", "s"}], ")"}]}]}], "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "l", ""], 
      SuperscriptBox[" ", "2"], 
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "c", ""]}], "2"], 
    SuperscriptBox["e", 
     RowBox[{"-", "\[LeftBracketingBar]", "s", "\[RightBracketingBar]", "/", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "c", ""]}]]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"1f18a6b5-fc6f-41a0-8bd2-3e14cb3ad6a3"],

Cell["\<\
with stationary variance C(0)=\[Sigma]_l\.b2\[Tau]_c/2 and integral time \
\[Tau]_c. The code implements the EXACT AR(1) discretisation of this SDE. The \
amplitude \[Sigma]_l is fixed by demanding that as \[Tau]_c\[RightArrow]0 the \
OU tendency \[Delta]\[Omega]=f\[CenterDot]dt converge to the SAME white \
forcing (so \[Epsilon] is unchanged and the two branches are directly \
comparable): a tendency driven by a stationary process with \[Integral]C ds = \
amp_l\.b2 is white-equivalent, and for OU \[Integral]C ds = \[Sigma]_l\.b2\
\[Tau]_c\.b2, hence\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1e5e59d5-0ce6-4818-b271-812b6604d6b9"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "l", ""], 
   SuperscriptBox[" ", "2"], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    SuperscriptBox["amp", "l"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "c", "2"]], "     ", "\[LongRightArrow]", 
   "     ", 
   RowBox[{"Var", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["f", "lm", ""], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"C", 
    RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]}], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    SuperscriptBox["amp", "l"], 
    RowBox[{"2", " ", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "c", ""]}]]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"33859af4-e3e2-4220-a5c9-304e45f7f1b9"],

Cell["\<\
The field is initialised at this stationary variance (no forcing transient). \
Coloured forcing removes the unphysical white-noise artefact and changes the \
injection statistics. In BOTH branches the forcing is added AFTER the \
deterministic Strang/ETDRK4 substep, so its \[Sqrt]dt scaling is preserved \
and it is never folded into the RK evaluations of N.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f2730c86-9c59-4753-8318-26d5b4af8ffb"],

Cell["\<\
References: Maltrud & Vallis (1991) J. Fluid Mech. 228, 321; Constantinou, \
Farrell & Ioannou (2014) J. Atmos. Sci. 71, 1818.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"f9960b52-244e-470c-8b0c-b7749590d5ac"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["12.  Scale Analysis, Dealiasing and Cascade Diagnostics", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"c99cf3e0-0ae2-4c00-afd0-19b756ca759f"],

Cell["\<\
Improvements #1, #6, #8. Together these decide whether the model demonstrably \
produces jets and a dual cascade \[Dash] the project's stated goal.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"84a1e847-ff07-4ad0-9451-f976688c8520"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["12.1  The Rhines scale and the zonostrophy index", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"576fbcea-78ab-4bb7-98e9-049cd34d131c"],

Cell["\<\
Jets emerge when the inverse energy cascade runs from the forcing scale up to \
the Rhines scale and is halted there by \[Beta]. The Rhines wavenumber is \
where the eddy turnover rate matches the Rossby-wave frequency:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"71348a90-6aeb-4577-9b27-ff4c7cfc12c3"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["l", "R", ""], "=", 
   SqrtBox[
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]"}], "U"]], "     ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"\[Beta]", "=", 
     RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]"}], ",", " ", "R", "=", "1"}], ")"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"e0dd68ed-3102-4aff-a9b5-7b48c86dc0ff"],

Cell["\<\
with U the rms large-scale velocity. Whether jets are SHARP is measured by \
the zonostrophy index (Galperin, Sukoriansky et al. 2006):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"eec379e9-b268-435a-bbd0-457bdce167f2"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["R", "\[Beta]", ""], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    SubsuperscriptBox["k", "\[Beta]", ""], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["k", "R", ""]], ",", "     ", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["k", "\[Beta]", ""], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", 
     FractionBox[
      SuperscriptBox["\[Beta]", "3"], "\[Epsilon]"], ")"}], 
    RowBox[{"1", "/", "5"}]], ",", "     ", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["k", "R", ""], "=", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["l", "R", ""]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"73e82cfb-fc0b-47a8-9416-30bf8412225a"],

Cell["\<\
Regimes: R_\[Beta] \[GreaterTilde] 2.5 zonostrophic (sharp jets), \
1.5\[Dash]2.5 transitional, <1.5 friction-dominated (no jets). v6 forced at \
l_f\[TildeTilde]60\[Dash]80 with l_R\[TildeTilde]23 \[Dash] a separation of \
only 2.6, far too small, hence NO jets. v7 retunes to \[CapitalOmega]=6.5, \
forcing at l=100\[Dash]120, \[Mu]=0.01, giving the textbook ordering l_R(\
\[TildeTilde]10) < k_\[Beta](\[TildeTilde]26) < l_f(\[TildeTilde]110) and a \
design estimate R_\[Beta]\[TildeTilde]2.6 \[Dash] borderline zonostrophic. \
The energy balance that closes this is drag-dominated:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"52ac7a66-52da-45ee-bcbe-20b82444db73"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["E", "sat", ""], "=", 
   FractionBox["\[Epsilon]", 
    RowBox[{"2", "\[Mu]"}]], ",", "     ", "U", "=", 
   SqrtBox[
    FractionBox["\[Epsilon]", "\[Mu]"]]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"907b3e39-e80a-47b1-b6fe-2b2adc729048"],

Cell["\<\
These are design targets; they must be re-measured from a saturated run \
(improvement #2), which is why v7 spins up for \[GreaterEqual]5 drag times \
with an auto-stationarity guard (all of energy, enstrophy and zonal fraction \
must plateau to within 2% over a sliding window).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b0063a3e-783a-4a8c-90c6-7d1128411e6b"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["12.2  Resolution and Orszag 2/3 dealiasing", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"42488d6d-0a6f-4cd8-971c-3db8f745c1f5"],

Cell["\<\
A wider inertial range needs higher truncation (improvement #6: v7 uses T170 \
vs v6's T127). The quadratic Jacobian generates modes up to 2L, which would \
alias back onto the resolved band unless removed. The Orszag (1971) 2/3 rule \
keeps only the lowest 2/3 of representable wavenumbers; pyshtools' Driscoll\
\[Dash]Healy DH2 grid OVERSAMPLES (2(L+1) latitudes \[Times] 2(L+1) \
longitudes for degree L), so quadratic products are dealiased at this \
truncation \[Dash] verified to 0.07% against a 2\[Times]-padded reference \
(Section 8).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7fa75905-6128-4bae-bebb-2a57b7613be1"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["12.3  Spectral flux \[Dash] the direct evidence for a cascade", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"0e4acb1a-e6eb-43b4-8bba-e6b61a57bcef"],

Cell["\<\
A broad spectrum is merely CONSISTENT with a dual cascade; it does not prove \
one. The rigorous diagnostic is the spectral FLUX computed from the nonlinear \
transfer T(l) (the projection of \[Dash]J(\[Psi],\[Omega]+f) onto each \
degree; verify_v7.spectral_flux). Since \[CapitalSigma]_l T(l)=0, the \
cumulative flux across degree l is\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9381eda8-5591-4d54-a9b0-f0422f482230"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalPi]", "E", ""], 
   RowBox[{"(", "l", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["l", "'", ""], "=", "1"}], "l"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["T", "E", ""], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["l", "'", ""], ")"}]}], ",", "     ", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalPi]", "Z", ""], 
   RowBox[{"(", "l", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["l", "'", ""], "=", "1"}], "l"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["T", "Z", ""], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["l", "'", ""], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"3d4c5406-7b5b-4de0-a3d5-364f2b7a062d"],

Cell["\<\
\[CapitalPi]_E(l) is the net rate energy crosses from degrees \[LessEqual]l \
to degrees >l. The dual-cascade signature that PROVES an inverse cascade is:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7f191f19-92e6-45e0-b47c-c6c99a9202ad"],

Cell["\<\
\[CapitalPi]_E(l) < 0 for l BELOW the forcing band \[Dash] energy flows \
UP-scale (toward small l): the inverse energy cascade.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"be3adfdd-cfe0-4d16-817a-3f23c8960a04"],

Cell["\<\
\[CapitalPi]_Z(l) > 0 for l ABOVE the forcing band \[Dash] enstrophy flows \
DOWN-scale (toward large l): the forward enstrophy cascade.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"74e8ff8f-6994-4cbd-a012-b25cdd5a23bb"],

Cell["\<\
This is the theory of Kraichnan (1967) / Batchelor: in 2-D the two quadratic \
invariants (energy and enstrophy) cannot both cascade the same way, so energy \
goes up and enstrophy goes down from the injection scale. Measuring the two \
flux SIGNS is what lets the project make a defensible claim about jets.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"caf8a0d5-9645-4ae2-a5ff-67a503534f9b"],

Cell["\<\
References: Rhines (1975) J. Fluid Mech. 69, 417; Vallis & Maltrud (1993) J. \
Phys. Oceanogr. 23, 1346; Galperin & Read (eds.), Zonal Jets (CUP 2019); \
Orszag (1971) J. Atmos. Sci. 28, 1074; Kraichnan (1967) Phys. Fluids 10, \
1417; Boffetta & Ecke (2012) Annu. Rev. Fluid Mech. 44, 427.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"50176e16-41b0-4108-b8e3-b5c490eb4736"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["13.  Spectral Vanishing Viscosity", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"54e07bbe-9e09-4f08-8fd4-fd76684330d1"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #7 (scientific_improvements.md \[Section]7). The \[Del]\[Cedilla] \
hyperviscosity absorbs ~10% of the ENERGY (it should drain mostly enstrophy). \
Spectral vanishing viscosity (Tadmor 1989) is a cleaner small-scale sink: \
identically zero over the resolved/inertial range, switching on smoothly only \
near truncation. Unlike a plain Laplacian it does not damp the large scales; \
unlike a sharp cutoff it is smooth (no Gibbs); and being a genuine modified \
viscosity it supplies the entropy dissipation that guarantees convergence to \
the correct weak solution. It acts as a Laplacian viscosity \
\[Dash]\[Epsilon]_SVV(l)\[CenterDot]\[Lambda]\[Omega] with an l-dependent \
coefficient (config_v7 SVV_*):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e00b150c-65a6-47ad-96df-cca1d1eece26"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "SVV", ""], 
   RowBox[{"(", "l", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "0", ""], "\[CenterDot]", 
    RowBox[{"exp", 
     RowBox[{"[", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       SuperscriptBox[
        RowBox[{"(", 
         FractionBox[
          RowBox[{"L", "-", "l"}], 
          RowBox[{"l", "-", 
           SubsuperscriptBox["l", "cut", ""]}]], ")"}], "2"]}], "]"}]}]}], "     ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"l", ">", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["l", "cut", ""]}], ")"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"12ca3d07-1a0b-440d-94c8-49c4d3b8b816"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "and \[Epsilon]_SVV(l)=0 for l\[LessEqual]l_cut, with L=LMAX. The kernel is \
0 at l_cut, rises smoothly, and reaches \[Epsilon]_0 at the truncation. The \
standard cutoff is l_cut ~ \[Sqrt]L (Maday & Tadmor 1989): \[Sqrt]170\
\[TildeTilde]13. Matching the hyperviscous cutoff rate \[Nu]\[Lambda]_max",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", "4"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8553411c-cd1f-4722-9929-08ae9af9cb8d"],
 "\[TildeTilde]4 fixes \[Epsilon]_0\[TildeTilde]4/(170\[CenterDot]171)\
\[TildeTilde]1.4\[Times]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["10", 
   RowBox[{"-", "4"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "eb0fb450-0534-4c1a-8acf-cdd35086ddb3"],
 ". SVV can SUPPLEMENT \[Del]\[Cedilla] or, with NU_HYPER=0, REPLACE it as \
the sole small-scale sink."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"24a7bdfc-305b-48df-b97b-71218c1cc3b5"],

Cell["\<\
References: Tadmor (1989) SIAM J. Numer. Anal. 26, 30; Maday & Tadmor (1989) \
SIAM J. Numer. Anal. 26, 854; Jablonowski & Williamson (2011), in Numerical \
Techniques for Global Atmospheric Models (Springer).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"190016b8-6a43-4945-9dd1-1751565608b4"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
14.  Extended Barotropic Physics: Mean Flow, Topography, Deformation Radius\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"826a3d2c-613b-41d4-8992-b92f1e5e3c6f"],

Cell["\<\
Improvements #9\[Dash]#11 (scientific_improvements.md \[Section]\[Section]9\
\[Dash]11). Three OPTIONAL extra terms in the SAME barotropic solver, \
disabled by default so the base run is unchanged. Each adds genuine physics \
with a minimal code change.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"bd4f899b-ab01-4fad-af82-2faad24c17e5"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["14.1  Differential-rotation mean flow (Newtonian relaxation)", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"95dc481a-c19a-4a22-9df9-0af493a46960"],

Cell["\<\
The v6 cutaway's longitude 'shear' is a pure visualization twist, not \
dynamics. Instead relax the ZONAL-MEAN (m=0) vorticity toward a prescribed \
solar-like differential-rotation profile (Held\[Dash]Suarez 1994 core), so \
the mean shear is a real term that can go barotropically unstable and shed \
eddies. A fast-equator angular velocity\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"652c186d-f7a4-4f79-9ca0-f1d54ddd1f17"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[CapitalOmega]", 
    RowBox[{"(", "\[Phi]", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "0", ""], "-", 
    RowBox[{"\[CapitalDelta]\[CapitalOmega]", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["sin", "2"], "\[Phi]"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"8286eab5-9d0a-4ec6-8090-25856a8cba06"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "gives a zonal wind ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "77358f87-3a86-4570-820d-283e5583a123"],
 "(\[Phi]) = \[Delta]\[CapitalOmega](\[Phi])\[CenterDot]R cos\[Phi] in the \
co-rotating frame (\[Delta]\[CapitalOmega]=\[Dash]\[CapitalDelta]\
\[CapitalOmega] sin\.b2\[Phi]); from ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b4a27583-6132-44d0-ae7f-c9a450bf32ba"],
 "=\[Dash](1/R)\[PartialD]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["\[Psi]", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "94e3c7a1-3e07-4c9c-95da-5fd81eb94e3f"],
 "/\[PartialD]\[Phi] the target streamfunction and vorticity are"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a54d2115-ec53-4d72-bf8d-48305eb62d11"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox["\[Psi]", "_"], "target", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox["R", "2"], "\[CapitalDelta]\[CapitalOmega]"}], "3"], 
    SuperscriptBox["sin", "3"], "\[Phi]"}], ",", "     ", 
   SubsuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "_"], "target", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox["\[Psi]", "_"], "target", ""]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"ec0c38eb-a776-468f-b982-a322215c678c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "applied only to the m=0 modes (\[Del]\.b2 is diagonal, so ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "_"], "target"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c362232b-6f39-4d5a-bb39-9c056b35b732"],
 "_{l0} = \[Dash]l(l+1)",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   OverscriptBox["\[Psi]", "_"], "target"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5331172d-4c05-4235-8004-ada0ee7e35ae"],
 "_{l0}). The relaxation term (Held\[Dash]Suarez form) is"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2d021f1f-74b0-4e02-8c70-ba0ecb8ae184"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox[
      RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
       OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "_"]}], 
      RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "|"}], "relax"], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox["1", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "relax", ""]], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "_"], "-", 
      SubsuperscriptBox[
       OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "_"], "target", ""]}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"72a05dc2-1ca2-43a7-8396-b528654f1d52"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["14.2  Topographic \[Beta] / bottom relief", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"84c498b3-77d7-47b1-a2e3-e389ceafe37e"],

Cell["\<\
Add a FIXED topography h(\[Theta],\[Phi]) to the potential vorticity, so the \
quantity advected by the flow becomes\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7d2cf281-c491-4ae7-a2e3-41c596ee12b9"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"q", "=", "\[Omega]", "+", "f", "+", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["f", "0", ""], "h"}], "H"], "\[Congruent]", "\[Omega]",
    "+", "f", "+", "\[Eta]"}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"519e817c-bc60-4af6-b5af-d7e603c991b9"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "with the stationary topographic vorticity \[Eta](\[Theta],\[Phi]) = f_0 \
h/H. The tendency \[Dash]J(\[Psi],q) then splits as \
\[Dash]J(\[Psi],\[Omega]+f) \[Dash] J(\[Psi],\[Eta]): the ONLY change is an \
extra advection of the fixed field \[Eta] by the flow. \[Eta] is an external \
PV source, NOT flow vorticity, so the streamfunction inversion \
\[Psi]=\[Del]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"-", "2"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9857cce2-be97-4213-978f-9ef52ca79074"],
 "\[Omega] is unchanged. Physically the stationary PV-gradient \[Del]\[Eta] \
radiates topographic Rossby waves, exerts form drag, and can anchor standing \
eddies / lock jets \[Dash] breaking the artificial zonal symmetry. In the \
code \[Eta] is a few low-order harmonics (config_v7 TOPO_MODES, e.g. an \
l=2,m=0 belt + an l=3,m=2 ridge; only l\[GreaterEqual]1 is dynamical)."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"73cb25d8-2659-417f-a031-c1a03417f0bf"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["14.3  Equivalent-barotropic model: finite deformation radius", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"ac3067fa-f84c-4875-90b8-1d074eeef384"],

Cell["\<\
Promote the PV inversion to the free-surface / reduced-gravity form by adding \
one diagonal term, introducing an intrinsic length scale L_d (the Rossby \
radius of deformation):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1f248dbe-97d1-42e4-94f8-45f556d4649d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"q", "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Psi]", "-", 
   FractionBox["\[Psi]", 
    SubsuperscriptBox["L", "d", "2"]], 
   RowBox[{"(", "+", "f", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"347e73f4-2a17-4e13-a385-763137a4b31e"],

Cell["\<\
The prognostic field is now the PV anomaly q; only the inversion changes,\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"158ea910-2dbf-4a9b-95e0-8329fe6e6e9a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "lm", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox[
     SubsuperscriptBox["q", "lm", ""], 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"l", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}], "+", 
      RowBox[{"1", "/", 
       SubsuperscriptBox["L", "d", "2"]}]}]]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"2743f68a-97e5-4280-9049-f63b0833f6b7"],

Cell["\<\
(was \[Dash]q_lm/[l(l+1)]). With finite L_d the inverse cascade halts at L_d \
as well as at the Rhines scale, giving more realistic jet widths. \
DEFORMATION_RADIUS=None recovers the rigid-lid barotropic model \
byte-for-byte; L_d\[TildeTilde]0.2 (1/L_d\.b2=25, comparable to l(l+1) at l\
\[TildeTilde]4\[Dash]5) bites at planetary scales.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0006fd21-ec63-468e-abf4-f301201fa646"],

Cell["\<\
References: Held & Suarez (1994) Bull. Amer. Meteorol. Soc. 75, 1825; Vallis \
& Maltrud (1993) J. Phys. Oceanogr. 23, 1346; Rhines (1975) J. Fluid Mech. \
69, 417; Vallis (2017) \[Section]\[Section]9, 14.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"cca2dd0f-7b4d-4af0-a1e8-f0dcc20d0d61"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
15.  Two-Layer Quasi-Geostrophic Model (Baroclinic Instability)\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"d4de58d3-220c-4009-a311-aac76d068db0"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #12 (two_layer_qg.py). The minimal model in which jets arise \
SELF-CONSISTENTLY from an internal energy source \[Dash] baroclinic \
instability of an imposed vertical shear \[Dash] rather than from ad-hoc \
stochastic forcing. Two layers of resting depth H_1 (upper), H_2 (lower), \
coupled across a density interface (reduced gravity g' = g\[CapitalDelta]\
\[Rho]/\[Rho]). Each layer has a streamfunction \[Psi]_i and a QG potential \
vorticity:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f595b477-f05b-49da-844f-b83d86a4b9bd"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["q", "1", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], 
       SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "1", ""], "+", "f", "+", 
       RowBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["F", "1", ""], 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{
          SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "2", ""], "-", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "1", ""]}], ")"}]}]}], ",", "    ", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["F", "1", ""], "=", 
      FractionBox[
       SubsuperscriptBox["f", "0", "2"], 
       RowBox[{"g", "'", " ", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["H", "1", ""]}]]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["q", "2", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], 
       SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "2", ""], "+", "f", "+", 
       RowBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["F", "2", ""], 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{
          SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "1", ""], "-", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "2", ""]}], ")"}]}]}], ",", "    ", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["F", "2", ""], "=", 
      FractionBox[
       SubsuperscriptBox["f", "0", "2"], 
       RowBox[{"g", "'", " ", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["H", "2", ""]}]]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"2359f641-1f81-4898-89d1-0592a2587ede"],

Cell["\<\
The stretching terms F_i(\[Psi]_j\[Dash]\[Psi]_i) are vortex-stretching by \
the interface displacement. Each layer materially conserves its PV up to \
forcing/dissipation:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c5ecfd81-f3a7-4bab-8695-2ce563229351"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["q", "1", ""]}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{"J", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "1", ""], ",", 
         SubsuperscriptBox["q", "1", ""]}], ")"}]}], "=", "\[ScriptCapitalF]",
       "+", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalD]", "1", ""]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["q", "2", ""]}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{"J", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "2", ""], ",", 
         SubsuperscriptBox["q", "2", ""]}], ")"}]}], "=", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalD]", "2", ""]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"e042d396-3d0e-44ee-b5cb-6eabc23c050a"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["15.1  Imposed shear as the energy source", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"80526d81-414a-447b-a5bd-649bc8b68004"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Split each field into a fixed background + perturbation. The background is \
solid-body rotation ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox["\[CapitalPsi]", "i"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7ad6defd-1f14-48cc-b787-d417c719d063"],
 " = \[Dash]U_i sin\[Phi] (a pure Y_10). Because ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox["\[CapitalPsi]", "i"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "66d999d8-5a78-47b2-8481-7e3ece6167c6"],
 " \[Proportional] sin\[Phi], so is Q_i, and J(",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox["\[CapitalPsi]", "i"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c6334a7b-52dc-4328-9d02-53fd2cf5da13"],
 ",Q_i)=J(sin\[Phi],sin\[Phi])=0: the background is an EXACT steady solution \
for any U_1,U_2. The vertical shear U_1\[Dash]U_2 tilts the interface and \
stores available potential energy; perturbations tap it. The \
Charney\[Dash]Stern necessary condition for instability is that the \
meridional PV gradient dQ_i/d\[Phi] change sign between layers, which the \
F_i(U_i\[Dash]U_j) term arranges once the shear exceeds a \[Beta]-dependent \
critical value (Phillips 1954)."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8f006ad2-f719-4882-b3d6-7819cd85c727"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["15.2  Layer coupling: 2\[Times]2 PV inversion", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a3c13022-ddc3-4e80-8818-448093f63bf6"],

Cell["\<\
With \[Del]\.b2\[RightArrow]\[Dash]\[Lambda], \[Lambda]=l(l+1), the \
perturbation inversion q = M\[Psi] is, per (l,m), a 2\[Times]2 system:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8f14c9cb-eeaf-4bbd-9b07-277a5062626c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"M", "=", 
   RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
      {
       RowBox[{"-", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", "+", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["F", "1", ""]}], ")"}]}], 
       SubsuperscriptBox["F", "1", ""]},
      {
       SubsuperscriptBox["F", "2", ""], 
       RowBox[{"-", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", "+", 
          SubsuperscriptBox["F", "2", ""]}], ")"}]}]}
     }], ")"}], ",", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"det", " ", "M"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", "+", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["F", "1", ""], "+", 
      SubsuperscriptBox["F", "2", ""]}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"7c882fea-c655-4516-be04-469aa4f6da85"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "so \[Psi]=M",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"-", "1"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "736824db-d143-4465-a50f-c8c4732a9b19"],
 "q per mode (det=0 only at l=0, the gauge, set to zero). The coupling \
k_d\.b2 \[Congruent] F_1+F_2 defines the internal deformation wavenumber. \
Energetically, total E = \[CapitalSigma]_i \.bd \
H_i\[Integral]|\[Del]\[Psi]_i|\.b2 + \.bd(f_0\.b2/g')\[Integral](\[Psi]_1\
\[Dash]\[Psi]_2)\.b2, the last term the APE; baroclinic instability converts \
mean APE \[Rule] eddy energy \[Rule] barotropic jets \[Dash] the signature is \
barotropic KE growing at the expense of the shear."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5fe34bb5-31dd-43fb-87bd-c0a2fc19f1ca"],

Cell["\<\
References: Phillips (1954) Tellus 6, 273; Panetta (1993) J. Atmos. Sci. 50, \
2073; Salmon, Lectures on Geophysical Fluid Dynamics (Oxford, 1998).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"0d1f3591-b1e9-4746-86d8-890e69b4611d"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["16.  Rotating Shallow-Water Equations on the Sphere", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"dd2d1948-36b0-44aa-aeda-de4c19a6e73b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Improvement #13 (shallow_water.py). Advance from one non-divergent \
vorticity equation to the full shallow-water system, restoring horizontal \
DIVERGENCE, GRAVITY WAVES and GEOSTROPHIC ADJUSTMENT \[Dash] the next rung \
above barotropic. In vector-invariant form, for layer height h and velocity \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c8abb434-49cb-49e6-b05c-20ee2a65a691"],
 " on a unit sphere:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dba88d20-e133-4958-9b42-6e7afd25e36d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "h"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[CenterDot]", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"h", " ", 
         OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], ")"}]}], "=", "0", "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", "mass", ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
        OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"f", "+", "\[Zeta]"}], ")"}], 
       OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[Cross]", 
       OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], "+", 
      RowBox[{"\[Del]", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"\[CapitalPhi]", "+", "K"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
      "\[ScriptCapitalD]", "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", "momentum", ")"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"7a6c5f2a-54ee-4797-865b-7c4f03dfaa5d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "with geopotential \[CapitalPhi]=gh, kinetic energy K=\.bd|",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a12dd005-2130-4209-94c5-408a6c0849bf"],
 "|\.b2, relative vorticity \[Zeta]=",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["z", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e58c5412-0e1f-48a8-8b50-e283e1aa1173"],
 "\[CenterDot]\[Del]\[Cross]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "0952ab00-2e15-4b8f-87f7-3b4885c1779a"],
 ", and f=2\[CapitalOmega]sin\[Phi]. Taking ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["z", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bba994a2-c754-4247-8fd4-5b8e2acad10c"],
 "\[CenterDot]\[Del]\[Cross] and \[Del]\[CenterDot] of the momentum equation \
gives a closed system for the prognostic scalars vorticity \[Zeta], \
divergence \[Delta], and height h:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a12d4a47-2ea4-4a6e-b0ed-50d2cec07b43"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Zeta]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       RowBox[{"J", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ",", "\[Eta]"}], ")"}]}]}], "-", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Eta]"}], "\[CenterDot]", 
       RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Chi]"}]}], "-", 
      RowBox[{"\[Eta]", " ", "\[Delta]"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Delta]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"J", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[Eta]", ",", "\[Chi]"}], ")"}]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Eta]"}], "\[CenterDot]", 
        RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Psi]"}]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{"\[Eta]", " ", "\[Zeta]"}], "-", 
       RowBox[{
        SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[CapitalPhi]", "+", "K"}], ")"}]}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "h"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       RowBox[{"J", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ",", "h"}], ")"}]}], "-", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"\[Del]", "h"}], "\[CenterDot]", 
        RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Chi]"}]}], "-", 
       RowBox[{"h", " ", "\[Delta]"}]}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"2d4633d6-9d9b-4647-b38a-4e69f741b8ab"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "with \[Eta]=\[Zeta]+f the absolute vorticity, and the velocity recovered by \
the Helmholtz decomposition \[Psi]=\[Del]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"-", "2"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7fbc44c3-4e63-4329-b672-561a26955da3"],
 "\[Zeta], \[Chi]=\[Del]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"-", "2"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f7b19d98-c010-472e-aa09-9d79caa279dc"],
 "\[Delta], ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9a9d29ca-860a-4d91-9db6-441e60d0ffdd"],
 "=",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["z", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bc66cee4-dd5e-4c01-983a-14289e9dcd7c"],
 "\[Cross]\[Del]\[Psi]+\[Del]\[Chi]. In the NON-DIVERGENT limit (\[Delta]=\
\[Chi]=0) the vorticity equation collapses to \
\[PartialD]\[Zeta]/\[PartialD]t=\[Dash]J(\[Psi],\[Zeta]+f) \[Dash] the \
barotropic model, which the code checks. The \[Dash]\[Del]\.b2\[CapitalPhi] \
term and the \[Dash]h\[Delta] mass term are the two sides of the gravity-wave \
/ geostrophic-adjustment mechanism absent from barotropic."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"845e1902-c340-469f-b334-9314788169d7"],

Cell["\<\
Verification uses Williamson et al. (1992) test case 2 \[Dash] global steady \
solid-body rotation, an exact time-independent solution (gradient-wind \
balance) for which all three tendencies must vanish to truncation error.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"796abda2-5df6-4b4f-9b30-39449ec0237b"],

Cell["\<\
References: Williamson et al. (1992) J. Comput. Phys. 102, 211; Galewsky, \
Scott & Polvani (2004) Tellus A 56, 429; Bourke (1972) Mon. Wea. Rev. 100, \
683.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"63068388-c42e-4918-8588-2caba6510cd4"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["17.  Two-Dimensional Magnetohydrodynamics (Barotropic MHD)", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"a752e912-4c45-498c-ae84-44a77c6d9fb1"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #14 (mhd_barotropic.py). Add a magnetic field and the Lorentz \
force \[Dash] the physically correct direction for the SOLAR framing, since \
in the tachocline a toroidal field suppresses the inverse cascade and can \
quench or reorganise jets. In 2-D both the velocity and the magnetic field \
derive from scalar potentials:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c2d2a363-924a-42da-b615-f0a78467ff8c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[Cross]", 
    RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Psi]"}]}], ",", "     ", "\[Omega]", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Psi]"}], ";", "        ", 
   OverscriptBox["B", "\[RightVector]"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox["z", "^"], "\[Cross]", "\[Del]", "A"}], ",", "     ", "j", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "A"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"b0d4e30a-5459-4144-aae2-4697c4ed7de7"],

Cell["\<\
where A is the magnetic flux function and j the out-of-plane current density \
(units \[Rho]=\[Mu]_0=1). The incompressible MHD equations reduce to TWO \
coupled advection equations \[Dash] a vorticity equation with a Lorentz \
tension, and an induction equation for A:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a7dc390a-f4ed-46ba-b9c5-e924fb416398"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Omega]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{"J", 
       RowBox[{"(", "\[Psi]", ",", 
        RowBox[{"\[Omega]", "+", "f"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
      RowBox[{"J", 
       RowBox[{"(", "A", ",", "j", ")"}]}], "+", "\[Nu]", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Omega]"}], "+", "F", "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", "vorticity", ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "A"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{"J", 
       RowBox[{"(", "\[Psi]", ",", "A", ")"}]}], "=", 
      RowBox[{"\[Eta]", " ", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "A"}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", "induction", ")"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"b35bed4b-1306-44ed-9611-ab419a28363c"],

Cell["\<\
with f=2\[CapitalOmega]sin\[Phi], \[Nu] the (hyper)viscosity, \[Eta] the \
magnetic diffusivity. BOTH the advection J(\[Psi],\[CenterDot]) and the \
Lorentz tension J(A,j) use the SAME spherical Jacobian primitive \[Dash] the \
magnetic tension is the Jacobian of the flux function with the current, \
exactly analogous to vorticity advection. (Sign convention: the \
self-consistent choice is j=\[Del]\.b2A with tension \
+J(A,j)=+J(A,\[Del]\.b2A), which gives \[Sigma]\.b2=+(k\[CenterDot]v_A)\.b2>0 \
\[Dash] restoring Alfv\[EAcute]n waves, not a spurious instability.)\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"271a2949-1083-47ce-ac18-98b63367a048"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["17.1  Ideal invariants and Alfv\[EAcute]n waves", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"6e15e54d-1f4c-44f2-bd23-e348d01078b1"],

Cell["\<\
In the ideal limit (\[Nu]=\[Eta]=F=0) 2-D MHD conserves three quadratic \
invariants, all checked by the code:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"31f785ff-3d38-4acd-a40d-1cb41c866c90"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{"E", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       FractionBox["1", "2"], "\[Integral]", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
          OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], 
          SuperscriptBox["\[RightBracketingBar]", "2"]}], "+", 
         RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
          OverscriptBox["B", "\[RightVector]"], 
          SuperscriptBox["\[RightBracketingBar]", "2"]}]}], ")"}], 
       "d\[CapitalOmega]"}], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       FractionBox["1", "2"], 
       UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", "lm", ""], "\[Lambda]", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         SuperscriptBox[
          SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "lm", ""], "2"], "+", 
         SuperscriptBox[
          SubsuperscriptBox["A", "lm", ""], "2"]}], ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"\[LeftAngleBracket]", 
       SuperscriptBox["A", "2"], "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", "lm", ""], 
       SuperscriptBox[
        SubsuperscriptBox["A", "lm", ""], "2"]}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"mean", "-", "square", " ", "flux"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["H", "c", ""], "=", 
      RowBox[{"\[Integral]", 
       OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", 
       OverscriptBox["B", "\[RightVector]"], "d\[CapitalOmega]"}], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", "lm", ""], "\[Lambda]", 
       SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "lm", ""], 
       SubsuperscriptBox["A", "lm", ""]}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"cross", "-", "helicity"}], ")"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"517efa8c-cd47-4e97-b45b-8e03d9c7b0b5"],

Cell["\<\
Linearising the ideal equations about a background field B_0 gives transverse \
oscillations at the Alfv\[EAcute]n frequency\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fa2fc971-0fd1-44fa-ad8d-6fc3efccdd1a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "A", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox["k", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", 
     OverscriptBox[
      SubscriptBox["v", "A"], "\[RightVector]"]}], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], 
   ",", "     ", 
   OverscriptBox[
    SubscriptBox["v", "A"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", 
   OverscriptBox[
    SubscriptBox["B", "0"], "\[RightVector]"], "    ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"\[Rho]", "=", "1"}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",\

 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"5b756488-350f-4149-8ab4-e916b9c59ad0"],

Cell["\<\
\[Omega]_A \[Proportional] |B_0| and \[Omega]_A \[Proportional] k \[Dash] the \
defining dispersion of Alfv\[EAcute]n waves. The code verifies the four \
robust signatures: the perturbation OSCILLATES (bounded, not growing); \
kinetic and magnetic energy EXCHANGE periodically at fixed total; the \
frequency scales LINEARLY with field strength; and with the perturbation \
wavenumber.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2a9f444c-55eb-4e5d-9e78-fd21d62258ee"],

Cell["\<\
References: Biskamp (2003), Magnetohydrodynamic Turbulence (CUP); Tobias, \
Diamond & Hughes (2007) ApJ 667, L113; Gilman (2000) ApJ 544, L79 \
(shallow-water MHD).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"7219e9ab-a043-4397-b8ea-3deef0e10226"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
18.  Boussinesq Rayleigh\[Dash]B\[EAcute]nard Convection in a Rotating Shell\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"3a15f761-364a-4830-b5f9-fa140fb89c46"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Improvement #15 (boussinesq_shell.py). The MINIMAL TRUE convection model. \
Where improvements #1\[Dash]#14 all evolve a single 2-D scalar with NO \
buoyancy, this adds the three ingredients that make the problem convection: a \
temperature perturbation \[CapitalTheta] with its own evolution equation, a \
BUOYANCY FORCE driving the flow, and a vertical velocity (a 3-D \
poloidal/toroidal field). Governing equations in a shell r_i<r<r_o, gravity \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["g", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7a301f4e-eaa5-4bc7-96eb-20c81533dd77"],
 "=\[Dash]g",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["r", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "25532072-f880-4f59-8182-e121335fda63"],
 ", rotation \[CapitalOmega]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["z", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e410cfe5-ce34-462e-8546-b1b28d957c3e"],
 ", with control numbers Ra (Rayleigh), Ek (Ekman), Pr (Prandtl):"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"94346321-e528-4854-ba05-3a9a467f25a2"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[CapitalTheta]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{
       OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", "\[Del]", 
       "\[CapitalTheta]"}], "=", 
      RowBox[{"\[Kappa]", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[CapitalTheta]"}], "+", 
      RowBox[{"S", 
       RowBox[{"(", "r", ")"}]}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Omega]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "+", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", "\[Del]"}], 
        ")"}], "\[Omega]"}], "-", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         OverscriptBox["\[Omega]", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", 
         "\[Del]"}], ")"}], 
       OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], "=", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       FractionBox[
        RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]"}], "Ek"], 
       FractionBox[
        RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", 
         OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], 
        RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "z"}]]}], "+", 
      RowBox[{"Ra", " ", "Pr", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         OverscriptBox["r", "^"], "\[Cross]", "\[Del]", "\[CapitalTheta]"}], 
        ")"}]}], "+", 
      RowBox[{"Pr", " ", 
       SuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "2"], "\[Omega]"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"0251f9ec-de63-4b2e-bf76-439648deba29"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The buoyancy term Ra\[CenterDot]Pr\[CenterDot](",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["r", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "99818d49-9f6e-4bed-b34a-9e330f6071cf"],
 "\[Cross]\[Del]\[CapitalTheta]) is the curl of the buoyancy force \[Rho]'",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["g", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1d8da04d-8587-43ec-968a-c3f0bb34bc89"],
 "\[Proportional]\[CapitalTheta]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["r", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "357cef9d-7783-497c-b0c3-983457eb65fd"],
 "; the (2\[CapitalOmega]/Ek)\[PartialD]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a5d59613-3787-45a1-bb3c-db1e99388f2d"],
 "/\[PartialD]z term is the curl of the Coriolis force. S(r) = \[Dash]w\
\[ThinSpace]d",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["T", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "be21b173-a5d1-4eec-b647-8bbc80e98c1f"],
 "/dr is the background heating."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"81dc5f61-f5f6-4589-9160-101221299df0"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["18.1  Linear onset \[Dash] the Chandrasekhar eigenvalue problem", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"fe36027a-1518-48bd-9e54-2701ecc4f957"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Linearising about rest and projecting on a horizontal planform of \
wavenumber a, the marginal-stability amplitudes of vertical velocity W, \
vertical vorticity \[Zeta] and temperature \[CapitalTheta] obey \
(Chandrasekhar 1961, D=d/dz, Ta=Ek",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"-", "2"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "80f38d49-6fcf-4983-b4c8-46a1e39fc180"],
 " the Taylor number):"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fbaedbae-3231-443a-8c77-d933e0c3d025"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox[
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{
         SuperscriptBox["D", "2"], "-", 
         SuperscriptBox["a", "2"]}], ")"}], "2"], "W", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["a", "2"], " ", "Ra", " ", "\[CapitalTheta]"}], "-", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["Ta", 
        RowBox[{"1", "/", "2"}]], "D", "\[Zeta]"}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"vertical", " ", "momentum"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{
        SuperscriptBox["D", "2"], "-", 
        SuperscriptBox["a", "2"]}], ")"}], "\[Zeta]", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["Ta", 
        RowBox[{"1", "/", "2"}]], "D", "W"}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"vertical", " ", "vorticity"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{
        SuperscriptBox["D", "2"], "-", 
        SuperscriptBox["a", "2"]}], ")"}], "\[CapitalTheta]", "=", 
      RowBox[{"-", "W"}], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", "heat", ")"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"3e8dbfc0-5004-4ea6-960b-f7a4b24a7236"],

Cell["\<\
Eliminating \[Zeta] and \[CapitalTheta] gives the sixth-order scalar \
eigenvalue problem whose lowest eigenvalue over the planform a is the \
critical Rayleigh number Ra_c:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"60636ed2-b93f-400c-a80d-8a709df0ffc6"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["D", "2"], "-", 
       SuperscriptBox["a", "2"]}], ")"}], "3"], "W"}], "+", 
   RowBox[{"Ta", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["D", "2"], "W"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    SuperscriptBox["a", "2"], "Ra", " ", "W"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"dac7f239-b9b1-4d3d-a017-f61e18f53486"],

Cell["\<\
With fixed-temperature plates, the mechanical boundary conditions fix the \
classic benchmarks (solved by Chebyshev collocation, N\[TildeTilde]40 \
collocation points, to machine accuracy):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e10b1d1e-d899-4e8b-9caa-30a33cdbc557"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Stress-free (\"free\"): W=D\.b2W=0, D\[Zeta]=0 \[LongRightArrow] Ra_c = 27\
\[Pi]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", "4"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bc1a9c42-e265-43f4-b491-2509e637176d"],
 "/4 = 657.511 (Ta=0)."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"50998ab8-c005-40d6-8c7e-38ca32ecd52c"],

Cell["No-slip (\"rigid\"): W=DW=0, \[Zeta]=0 \[LongRightArrow] Ra_c = \
1707.762 (Ta=0).", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"4cd452c5-1ed0-4448-862c-\
ba8ea0f981e8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Rapid rotation: Ra_c \[Proportional] Ek",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"-", "4"}], "/", "3"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "274a1ea9-f637-495e-a9e7-551ac41efdcd"],
 " \[Dash] rotation strongly stabilises convection and selects a narrow (a\
\[Proportional]Ek",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}], "/", "3"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a17c6c74-f906-441f-b290-b0b6e31b1b3a"],
 ") cell, the onset of the columnar (banana-cell) regime of Section 3.2."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"f49a4163-54a0-4bd6-8d5f-a2c7028b92fb"],

Cell["\<\
The convective NONLINEARITY is verified separately via the Saltzman (1962) / \
Lorenz (1963) Galerkin truncation \[Dash] the smallest self-contained system \
carrying the advective nonlinearity + buoyancy exchange \[Dash] which \
conserves energy in the dissipationless limit.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0660eacf-7b4b-47e1-ad0b-02e76482f704"],

Cell["\<\
References: Chandrasekhar (1961), Hydrodynamic and Hydromagnetic Stability \
(Oxford); Christensen & Aubert (2006) Geophys. J. Int. 166, 97; Gastine, \
Wicht & Aurnou (2013) Icarus 225, 156; Saltzman (1962) J. Atmos. Sci. 19, \
329; Lorenz (1963) J. Atmos. Sci. 20, 130.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"829ed381-2870-4edc-aaa8-c13f972374a1"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["19.  Anelastic Convection in a Stratified Shell", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"620c0b6d-8a01-46f6-b57b-f00ca2f831c4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Improvement #16 (anelastic_shell.py). Boussinesq treats the background \
density as uniform \[Dash] valid only for a thin layer. The solar convection \
zone spans ~14 density scale heights (\[Rho] varies by ~10",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["0", "6"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "dfc04c86-6f15-4fba-9747-ed6f7b852805"],
 " from base to photosphere), so Boussinesq is INVALID there. The anelastic \
approximation (Gough 1969; Braginsky & Roberts 1995) filters sound waves \
while retaining the strongly varying background density ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "dc7281c6-6ee6-447f-a5c3-e7fdc96843a4"],
 "(r). Its two defining consequences:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e0f33bb1-dfb1-420c-9f74-dd547887c21f"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["19.1  The anelastic mass constraint", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"ced5718b-65d2-497f-bc4a-a2b939137bc2"],

Cell["\<\
Continuity becomes a constraint on the MASS flux, not the velocity:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d74b43eb-199a-4131-acdc-34569ce7ae6a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[CenterDot]", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], 
      OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], ")"}]}], "=", "0", "     ", "\[LongRightArrow]",
    "     ", 
   RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[CenterDot]", 
    OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"], "\[CenterDot]", "\[Del]", 
    RowBox[{"ln", " ", 
     OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"]}]}], "\[NotEqual]", "0"}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"c2074971-307e-4f13-997e-c44c43c5f0f7"],

Cell["\<\
so the velocity itself is COMPRESSIBLE \[Dash] this is what produces the \
up/down-flow ASYMMETRY of stratified convection: broad slow upflows, narrow \
fast downdrafts. The constraint is enforced exactly by writing the mass flux \
(not the velocity) with poloidal/toroidal scalars,\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c8879471-a0ea-4826-803e-e4beaeb989c8"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], 
    OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Cross]", 
     RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Cross]"}]}], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"P", " ", 
      OverscriptBox["r", "^"]}], ")"}]}], "+", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[Del]", "\[Cross]"}], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"T", " ", 
      OverscriptBox["r", "^"]}], ")"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"893276c7-8fb8-48cc-85a4-e0e731acf40b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "which makes \[Del]\[CenterDot](",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "07eb693a-aed1-415e-8378-8d438d868165"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5faac74c-b11f-4738-a3ec-43015a5491c0"],
 ") = \[Del]\[CenterDot](\[Del]\[Cross]\[CenterDot]) \[Congruent] 0 \
identically (verified to machine precision)."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"51b17ba7-bdb4-446a-aa6b-1a7c53997a7f"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["19.2  The polytropic reference state", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"4e3af89b-c1a9-454e-8ae4-c4b804d4a5a9"],

Cell["\<\
The background is a hydrostatic polytrope over N_\[Rho] density scale heights \
(Jones et al. 2011 anelastic benchmark). With aspect ratio \[Eta]=r_i/r_o, \
polytropic index n, gravity g\[Proportional]1/r\.b2, the dimensionless \
temperature \[Zeta](r) is linear in 1/r and the background fields are its \
powers:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fa97c39c-d388-4955-8d8a-a533f7ec108e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[Zeta]", 
    RowBox[{"(", "r", ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["c", "0", ""], "+", 
    RowBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["c", "1", ""], 
     FractionBox["d", "r"]}]}], ",", "        ", 
   OverscriptBox["T", "_"], "=", "\[Zeta]", ",", "     ", 
   OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["\[Zeta]", "n"], ",", "     ", 
   OverscriptBox["p", "_"], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox["\[Zeta]", 
    RowBox[{"n", "+", "1"}]]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"4096d355-7aa9-4fa4-b2f9-6e914f407b54"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "(d=r_o\[Dash]r_i; ideal gas ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["p", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b8e5cc9f-53e1-48d5-a84c-f1bf231f4667"],
 "=",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "018a42b7-9c14-44ab-94b7-99badd955540"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["T", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a7610c69-3f82-479d-9604-dc438b16585c"],
 " automatically). Then the number of density scale heights is exactly"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"83ff286b-d89f-4bbc-a424-2e742cbe45ba"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["N", "\[Rho]", ""], "=", 
   RowBox[{"ln", 
    RowBox[{"[", 
     FractionBox[
      RowBox[{
       OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["r", "i", ""], ")"}]}], 
      RowBox[{
       OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        SubsuperscriptBox["r", "o", ""], ")"}]}]], "]"}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"7c76f9d9-9bd5-49c4-b8a6-bcd1525c3c68"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "and hydrostatic balance d",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["p", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "552d76b7-4c98-4bf3-a7f2-5b455e29d7e3"],
 "/dr = \[Dash]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "87119457-2a47-40c4-b919-e7efafcd2131"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["g", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f6624cf2-ba67-41ea-a5ec-1ce9426b6852"],
 " holds. The polytrope is p\[Proportional]\[Rho]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"n", "+", "1"}], ")"}], "/", "n"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8537a071-d4dd-4d90-8a9a-51750387d45c"],
 "; it is exactly ISENTROPIC when n=n_ad=1/(\[Gamma]\[Dash]1) and \
SUPER-adiabatic (convectively unstable, d",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["s", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "775526ec-2b81-4ca5-b73c-4045646a51f1"],
 "/dr<0) when n<n_ad \[Dash] the physical regime for convection."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"87613854-6e7e-45df-9574-b5d21d46abe5"],

Cell["\<\
References: Gough (1969) J. Atmos. Sci. 26, 448; Braginsky & Roberts (1995) \
GAFD 79, 1; Jones et al. (2011) Icarus 216, 120; Lantz & Fan (1999) ApJS 121, \
247.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"cb7f388e-70b1-4796-b468-84d660583960"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["20.  Community Solvers: Rayleigh and Dedalus", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"298bf334-c143-4651-a1c1-1b9ab1442fc2"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #17 (rayleigh_dedalus_setup.py). Rather than hand-build a 3-D \
convection solver (years of development + verification risk), map the control \
parameters onto a VALIDATED community code: Rayleigh (Featherstone & Hindman \
2016, a pseudo-spectral anelastic convection/dynamo code) or Dedalus (Burns \
et al. 2020, a general spectral-PDE framework whose spherical bases express \
the shell system in a few dozen lines). The module emits ready-to-run input \
for either code from a single parameter object, with the SAME physics in \
both. The shared nondimensional convention:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7550d478-17ed-4f91-9b8c-4fe1dfdd21d4"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{"Ra", "=", 
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", " ", "g", " ", "\[CapitalDelta]T", " ", 
        SuperscriptBox["d", "3"]}], 
       RowBox[{"\[Nu]", " ", "\[Kappa]"}]], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"buoyancy", " ", 
        RowBox[{"vs", "."}], " ", "diffusion"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"Ek", "=", 
      FractionBox["\[Nu]", 
       RowBox[{"2", "\[CapitalOmega]", " ", 
        SuperscriptBox["d", "2"]}]], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"viscosity", " ", 
        RowBox[{"vs", "."}], " ", "rotation"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"Pr", "=", 
      FractionBox["\[Nu]", "\[Kappa]"], ",", "     ", "Pm", "=", 
      FractionBox["\[Nu]", "\[Eta]"], "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"thermal", ",", " ", "magnetic", " ", "Prandtl"}], ")"}]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{"\[Eta]", "=", 
      FractionBox[
       SubsuperscriptBox["r", "i", ""], 
       SubsuperscriptBox["r", "o", ""]], ",", "     ", "d", "=", 
      RowBox[{
       SubsuperscriptBox["r", "o", ""], "-", 
       SubsuperscriptBox["r", "i", ""]}], "=", "1", "     ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"aspect", " ", "ratio"}], ")"}]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"aa790fad-d205-46a1-8cf6-1cd449ef47fe"],

Cell["\<\
reference_type=1 is a Boussinesq shell (improvement #15); reference_type=2 is \
a polytropic anelastic shell (improvement #16) parameterised by N_\[Rho] and \
n. The module verifies that the Rayleigh namelist round-trips through a \
bundled parser (every control number reads back exactly), that the Dedalus \
script is valid Python whose parameter block exec's to the requested values, \
and that the Boussinesq\[LeftRightArrow]anelastic and \
no-slip\[LeftRightArrow]stress-free toggles propagate to both.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9a0c2098-9223-4f41-8977-56432fcb9280"],

Cell["\<\
References: Featherstone & Hindman (2016) ApJ 818, 32 (Rayleigh); Burns, \
Vasil, Oishi, Lecoanet & Brown (2020) Phys. Rev. Research 2, 023068 \
(Dedalus); Christensen et al. (2001) Phys. Earth Planet. Inter. 128, 25 \
(dynamo benchmark).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"bed36eb9-3629-4c44-a23c-bca5a94f60eb"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["21.  Coupling to the Model S Solar Stratification", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"1c415f37-6362-4bdb-83ce-61a5efc5be22"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #18 (model_s_stratification.py). Drive the convection of #15\
\[Dash]#17 with a REALISTIC solar background \[Dash] temperature, density, \
gravity and entropy vs. radius from a standard solar model \[Dash] rather \
than a constant or ad-hoc profile. The convective length scales, velocities \
and super-adiabaticity are all set by the true stratification, so Model S \
makes a simulation quantitatively comparable to helioseismology (0.713 \
\[LessEqual] r/R_\[CircleDot] \[LessEqual] 1.0). Gravity is not tabulated \
\[Dash] the CZ holds \[LessTilde]2% of the Sun's mass, so to ~1%\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"02814374-bd5e-49ce-9050-009352aa4f55"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"g", 
    RowBox[{"(", "r", ")"}]}], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"G", " ", 
     SubscriptBox["M", "\[CircleDot]"]}], 
    SuperscriptBox["r", "2"]], ",", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"g", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"r", "=", 
      SubscriptBox["R", "\[CircleDot]"]}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{"274", " ", 
    RowBox[{"m", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["s", 
      RowBox[{"-", "2"}]]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"128cb02e-6bb8-4f42-82b4-bea4519a6bf9"],

Cell["\<\
The bulk convection zone is nearly ISENTROPIC: the logarithmic gradient \
matches the adiabatic value,\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"999d3a0a-a9b2-494b-a4f6-593f81624cd5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"\[Del]", "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"d", " ", 
     RowBox[{"ln", " ", "T"}]}], 
    RowBox[{"d", " ", 
     RowBox[{"ln", " ", "P"}]}]], "\[TildeTilde]", 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Del]", "ad", ""], "=", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[Gamma]", "-", "1"}], "\[Gamma]"], "=", "0.4", "     ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"\[Gamma]", "=", 
     RowBox[{"5", "/", "3"}]}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"087a7594-c333-4666-99b6-8d0125b9a26f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "so d",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["s", "_"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e10c1419-a6f9-489e-b526-c1f069101198"],
 "/dr\[TildeTilde]0 with only a slight super-adiabatic deficit \[Dash] the \
small excess that actually drives the convection \[Dash] departing only in \
the thin radiative surface layer. Anchor values the profile reproduces (Model \
S / standard solar model):"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f0ff4289-407c-4800-a2a9-f69fc613b3d0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Base of CZ (x=0.713): T\[TildeTilde]2.18\[Times]10",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["0", "6"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "341e1fac-819c-4926-824b-944c9d6a71b1"],
 " K, \[Rho]\[TildeTilde]0.187 g cm",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"-", "3"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9b55978a-e311-46e4-a36c-918f85f0c820"],
 ", g\[TildeTilde]539 m s",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"-", "2"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8ec03ec8-4eb5-4683-8d31-91fabf5e5eb8"],
 "."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c2e6dadc-f391-4027-adda-39da474be42c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Photosphere (x=1.0): T\[TildeTilde]5.77\[Times]10",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["0", "3"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "6f238b72-a61f-414e-975a-16e2cf826da8"],
 " K, \[Rho]\[TildeTilde]2.5\[Times]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["10", 
   RowBox[{"-", "7"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "95bfbe1f-c523-4cb1-aa30-99a3f51c8ba5"],
 " g cm",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"-", "3"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "40e1454d-c5cd-4350-8e8f-94aa38d9ad49"],
 ", g\[TildeTilde]274 m s",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"-", "2"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "972e8bea-c28a-4801-b2cd-c58d0f2bdf96"],
 "."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9259deec-81f4-48ba-bce6-c3d9a3b685da"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Density scale heights across the CZ: ln[",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], "base"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "07315f47-08de-4a29-b9e6-e10fa56d9704"],
 "/",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   OverscriptBox["\[Rho]", "_"], "top"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "0422ce5c-f900-443b-83a5-c37cd94846de"],
 "] \[TildeTilde] 13.5 \[Dash] the deep, highly stratified envelope that \
makes the ANELASTIC model (#16), not Boussinesq, the correct reduced \
description."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"454bb6f2-640b-4c35-9699-f450db827d38"],

Cell["\<\
Honesty: this is a smooth fit to Model S anchored to published values, not \
the Model S data file itself; the thin surface ionization layers are \
approximate. For quantitative work, replace the bundled table with actual \
Model S / MESA output \[Dash] the interpolant API is unchanged.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4e50f857-144c-4a19-ba21-c7315b1ca4fb"],

Cell["\<\
References: Christensen-Dalsgaard et al. (1996) Science 272, 1286 (Model S); \
Miesch (2005) Living Rev. Solar Phys. 2, 1; Stix, The Sun (2nd ed., 2002).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"ac046214-a025-4040-8a0a-cb587d9f645b"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["22.  Lagrangian Transport and Finite-Time Lyapunov Exponents", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"5218d598-cade-4983-9c26-b0a038b002b0"],

Cell["\<\
Improvement #19 (lagrangian_ftle.py). A snapshot of vorticity is an EULERIAN \
object; it cannot say where fluid is stirred versus transported coherently. \
Advecting passive tracers with the (verified-correct) velocity field and \
computing FTLE extracts the Lagrangian coherent structures \[Dash] the \
material transport BARRIERS. On a rotating sphere the zonal JETS are exactly \
such barriers: fluid does not cross a jet core, so an FTLE ridge sits on each \
jet while the flanks mix. This turns the movie into evidence about transport.\
\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"13bbf837-24a9-4c93-9870-9f189da88266"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["22.1  The tracer equation", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"7108601a-237d-490d-9d04-8e3bc662d7d4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "With \[Psi]_lm=\[Dash]\[Omega]_lm/[l(l+1)] and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["u", "\[RightVector]"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bd12124f-2f74-45a3-b09c-0fd9fa518199"],
 "=",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox["z", "^"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "fc205026-a92f-4118-baaf-182786c877aa"],
 "\[Cross]\[Del]\[Psi], the colatitude/longitude velocity components (unit \
sphere) and the tracer ODE are"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fbcf3ce2-1d2b-4681-921f-b29048cbd2e5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["u", "\[Theta]"], "=", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       FractionBox["1", 
        RowBox[{"sin", "\[Theta]"}]], 
       FractionBox[
        RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Psi]"}], 
        RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Phi]"}]]}], ",", "     ", 
      SubscriptBox["u", "\[Phi]"], "=", 
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Psi]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Theta]"}]]}]},
    {
     RowBox[{
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Theta]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
      SubscriptBox["u", "\[Theta]"], ",", "        ", 
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "\[Phi]"}], 
       RowBox[{"\[PartialD]", "t"}]], "=", 
      FractionBox[
       SubscriptBox["u", "\[Phi]"], 
       RowBox[{"sin", "\[Theta]"}]]}]}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"cad11149-6b93-433c-a8e3-06661e21c5ab"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["22.2  The flow-map gradient and FTLE", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"b3e57f99-3d97-4dea-88f2-26500141a781"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Seed a uniform grid of tracers, advect for time T under the (snapshot) \
field, and form the flow-map (deformation) gradient F by finite-differencing \
neighbouring tracers, carrying the sphere metric (arc-lengths d\[Theta] and \
sin\[Theta]\[ThinSpace]d\[Phi]). With \[Sigma]_max the largest singular value \
of F (equivalently \[Sqrt]\[Lambda]_max of the right Cauchy\[Dash]Green \
tensor C=",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["F", "T"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7a5ef8f3-dc97-4987-b2a8-52b84417e03f"],
 "F), the FTLE is"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"82438dc5-1669-4b93-8a95-900f9b0bdda0"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "FTLE", ""], 
   RowBox[{"(", "x", ")"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["1", 
     RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", "T", "\[RightBracketingBar]"}]], 
    RowBox[{"ln", " ", 
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "max", ""], 
     RowBox[{"(", "x", ")"}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"1a2e5fa7-9be1-4201-96e5-6e79b6d4fdfa"],

Cell["\<\
Ridges of \[Sigma]_FTLE are the finite-time transport barriers \[Dash] and on \
a jet-bearing flow they trace the jet cores directly, a dynamical diagnostic \
no single vorticity snapshot provides.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3d907a6c-c2b2-46e5-b0fd-244f691c53f8"],

Cell["\<\
References: Haller (2015) Annu. Rev. Fluid Mech. 47, 137 (LCS review); \
Shadden, Lekien & Marsden (2005) Physica D 212, 271 (FTLE ridges as LCS).\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"a8508bc1-9d19-4460-9305-34f773afde41"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
23.  Honest Interior: the True (r/R)^l Evanescent Continuation\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"947fe318-e547-46fc-9466-b8b9a909a944"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Improvement #20 (honest_interior.py). The v6 renderer continued the surface \
field inward with a mixing-length-scaled factor (r/R)",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[")", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"l", "/", "L_ref"}], ")"}]]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bfa048f2-3fb8-43f9-a7bf-1902aba61e23"],
 " using L_ref=10, and painted the inner core ~32\[Times] amplified. Both \
OVERSTATE what a 2-D barotropic field can say about the deep interior. The \
mathematically honest continuation of a degree-l surface pattern that is \
regular at the origin is the interior solution of Laplace's equation:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"38d763aa-13bb-4442-9681-68f396f67759"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[CapitalPhi]", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"r", ",", "\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    UnderoverscriptBox["\[Sum]", "lm", ""], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      FractionBox["r", "R"], ")"}], "l"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Omega]", "lm", ""], 
    RowBox[{"Y", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"\[Theta]", ",", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}]}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"52ee9600-8973-4167-958c-98e15cf4f37b"],

Cell["\<\
\[Dash] NOT solved interior dynamics. It is EVANESCENT: high-l (small-scale) \
structure decays within a thin skin of depth ~R/l, while only the largest \
scales reach the base. The l/L_ref exponent with L_ref=10 inflates the \
e-folding depth by ~10\[Times]. For the forcing-scale modes (l\[TildeTilde]60\
\[Dash]80) the honest factor at the base r=0.71R is\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9f545a84-3bc1-47e7-9ec6-f8d3e232e18b"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", "0.71", ")"}], "l"], "\[TildeTilde]", 
   RowBox[{"4", "\[Times]", 
    SuperscriptBox["10", 
     RowBox[{"-", "11"}]]}], "     ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"l", "\[TildeTilde]", "60", "\[Dash]", "80"}], ")"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"d7b74551-d3ff-449e-852d-df1cb3f041de"],

Cell["\<\
i.e. the interior is essentially EMPTY. That is the correct answer: a 2-D \
barotropic model carries NO radial information, so any visible interior \
structure is decoration, not physics. The module therefore offers the honest \
alternatives named in the spec: (a) show ONLY the 2-D surface field, no \
interior; or (b) render the TRUE (r/R)^l continuation (surface-confined for \
forcing-scale modes). A genuine 3-D field requires items #15\[Dash]#17.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"13ef3156-d238-4225-9f4d-6a2cdb088e8f"],

Cell["\<\
References: project audits physics_audit.md and v6_critical_audit.md \
\[Section]\[Section]4.4, 5.1; for a genuine 3-D field see \
\[Section]\[Section]15\[Dash]17.\
\>", "Text",
 FontSlant->Italic,ExpressionUUID->"f8c088ce-bb42-4f65-bc01-0c3292cb6ffe"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["24.  Summary: From 2-D Turbulence Toward Solar Convection", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"26d8e687-9dc0-4ce8-b091-649ea7299220"],

Cell["\<\
The twenty improvements trace a deliberate arc. Tier A (\[Section]\[Section]9\
\[Dash]13) makes the barotropic model demonstrably do what it claimed: a wide \
forcing\[Dash]Rhines separation and controlled injection aimed at the \
zonostrophic regime, 2nd-/4th-order time stepping with exact linear \
treatment, a clean spectral sink, and \[Dash] decisively \[Dash] a direct \
FLUX measurement that distinguishes a real dual cascade from a merely \
broadened spectrum. Tier B (\[Section]\[Section]14\[Dash]17) adds genuine new \
physics: a self-consistent mean flow, topographic locking, a finite \
deformation radius, self-consistent baroclinic jets, gravity waves, and the \
solar-relevant Lorentz force. Tier C (\[Section]\[Section]18\[Dash]21) \
crosses the line into ACTUAL convection \[Dash] buoyancy, an energy equation, \
a radial dimension, correct anelastic stratification, and a real solar \
background. Tier D (\[Section]\[Section]22\[Dash]23) converts the output from \
illustration into evidence and removes the one remaining misleading element.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b9efbbbf-704d-447c-953c-db293ec9d8e2"],

Cell["\<\
The honest through-line: the numerics of the base solver are verified \
correct; the gaps were always physical SCOPE and run DISCIPLINE, not bugs. \
The single cheapest change with the largest scientific payoff remains items \
1+2+8 together \[Dash] run long enough, with wider scale separation, and \
MEASURE THE FLUX \[Dash] which alone lets the project make a defensible claim \
about jets. Everything from \[Section]18 onward is the honest destination if \
\"solar convection\" is to be more than a motivating label.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7f1b735c-626e-4f31-a842-6efac46f22e1"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

